, the HDI of Macau was 0.909 in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dsec.gov.mo/getAttachment/3fcdb33a-9238-44ca-8e4b-ebdb9c868e8e/E_MN_PUB_2016_Y.aspx|title=Macau in Figures, 2016|publisher=\u6fb3\u9580\u7d71\u8a08\u66a8\u666e\u67e5\u5c40(DSEC)|language=en|accessdate=2017-12-05}}</ref>}}\n  |{{KOR}}\n|-\n|1\n  |[[Beijing]]\n  | 0.894\n  |{{ESP}}\n|-\n  | \u2013\n  |{{Flagicon|ROC}} ''[[Taiwan]]''{{Efn|name=sar}}\n  | 0.880{{efn|In the 2018 Subnational Human Development Database (SHDD), where the HDIs of other administrative regions except Macao are acquired, Taiwan's HDI is 0.880.<ref name=\":02\"/> Yet, according to the Statistical Bureau of the [[Taiwan|Republic of China]], the HDI of Taiwan in 2017 was 0.907, close to those of [[Japan]] and [[South Korea]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stat.gov.tw/public/Data/81030161446GEYJEAG4.pdf|title=\u570b\u60c5\u7d71\u8a08\u901a\u5831\uff08\u7b2c 206 \u865f\uff09|author=\u884c\u653f\u9662\u4e3b\u8a08\u7e3d\u8655\u7d9c\u5408\u7d71\u8a08\u8655|access-date=2019-05-05|language=zh-ttw}}</ref>}}\n  |{{EST}}\n|-\n|2\n  |[[Shanghai]]\n  | 0.867\n  |{{UAE}}\n|-\n|3\n  |[[Tianjin]]\n  | 0.850\n  |{{PRT}}\n|-\n|4\n  |[[Jiangsu]]\n  | 0.802\n  |{{MYS}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"color:#0c0;\" | High human development\n|-\n|5\n  |[[Guangdong]]\n  | 0.791\n  |{{ALB}}\n|-\n|6\n  |[[Zhejiang]]\n  | 0.789\n  |{{GEO}}\n|-\n|7\n  |[[Liaoning]]\n  | 0.777\n  |{{KNA}}\n|-\n|8\n  |[[Inner Mongolia]]\n  | 0.774\n  |{{BIH}}\n|-\n|9\n|[[Jilin]]\n  | 0.767\n  |{{THA}}\n|-\n|10\n|[[Shandong]]\n  | 0.765\n|{{THA}}\n|-\n|11\n  |[[Fujian]]\n  | 0.764\n  |{{BRA}}\n|-\n|12\n  |[[Hubei]]\n  | 0.762\n  |{{COL}}\n|-\n|13\n  |[[Chongqing]]\n  | 0.759\n  |{{DZA}}, {{MKD}} or {{ARM}}\n|- style=\"background:#e6e6e6\"\n  | \u2013\n  |'''{{flag|China}} (Average)'''\n  |'''0.758'''\n  |{{PER}}\n|-\n|14\n  |[[Shaanxi]]\n  | 0.756\n  |{{ECU}} or {{AZE}}\n|-\n|15\n|[[Hunan]]\n  | 0.751\n| rowspan=\"3\" |{{UKR}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |16\n|[[Shanxi]]\n  | 0.750\n|