 the Human Body'', Los Angeles: UCLA Museum of Cultural History\n* Sanders, Clinton R. (1989) ''Customizing the Body: the Art and Culture of Tattooing''. Philadelphia: Temple University Press\n* Sinclair, A. T. (1909) \"Tattooing of the North American Indians\", in ''American Anthropologist'' 1909/11, No. 3, p.&nbsp;362\u2013400\n* Thompson, Beverly Yuen (2015) ''[https://nyupress.org/books/978-0-8147-8920-9/ Covered in Ink: Tattoos, Women and the Politics of the Body]'', New York University Press. {{ISBN|9780814789209}}\n* Wianecki, Shannon (2011) [https://web.archive.org/web/20110712031242/http://www.mauimagazine.net/Maui-Magazine/July-August-2011/Marked/ \"Marked\" ''[[Maui No Ka 'Oi Magazine]]''.]\n\n; Popular and artistic\n* Green, Terisa. ''Ink: The Not-Just-Skin-Deep Guide to Getting a Tattoo'' {{ISBN|0-451-21514-1}}\n* Green, Terisa. ''The Tattoo Encyclopedia: A Guide to Choosing Your Tattoo'' {{ISBN|0-7432-2329-2}}\n* Krak\u00f3w, Amy. ''Total Tattoo Book'' {{ISBN|0-446-67001-4}}\n\n; Medical\n* {{Citation |title = CDC's Position on Tattooing and HCV Infection |url = https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/C/cFAQ.htm#cFAQ10 |accessdate = 12 June 2006 |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] }}\n* {{Citation |title = Body Art (workplace hazards) |url = https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/topics/body_art/| accessdate=15 September 2008 |publisher=[[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]] }}\n* {{Citation |title = Tattoos and Permanent Makeup |work=CFSAN/Office of Cosmetics and Colors (2000; updated 2004, 2006) |url = https://www.fda.gov/Cosmetics/ProductandIngredientSafety/ProductInformation/ucm108530.htm |accessdate = 12 June 2006 |publisher=[[United States Food and Drug Administration]]}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Haley |first=R. W. |last2=Fischer |first2=R. P. |title=Commercial tattooing as a potential source of hepatitis C infection |journal=Medicine |date=March 2000 |volume=80 |issue=2 |pages=134\u2013151 |doi = 10.1097/00005792-200103000-00006 |pmid=11307589 }}\n* Paola Piccinini, Laura Contor, Ivana Bianchi, Chiara Senaldi, Sazan Pakalin: ''Safety of tattoos and permanent make-up'', [[Joint Research Centre]], 2016, {{ISBN|978-92-79-58783-2}}, [[doi:10.2788/011817]].\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Library resources box |by = no |onlinebooks = no |about = yes |wikititle = tattoo }}\n* {{Wikiquote-inline}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|Tattoos}}\n* {{Wikisource-inline|Tattooing}}\n* [http://video.pbs.org/video/2219469018 Tattoos, The Permanent Art] Documentary produced by [[Off Book (web series)]]\n* [https://www.google.com/culturalinstitute/exhibit/history-ink/wQx72HUG?hl=en History, Ink] produced by Meghan Glass Hughes for The Valentine Richmond History Center\n\n{{-}}\n{{Tattoo}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Tattooing| ]]\n[[Category:1970s fashion]]\n[[Category:1980s fashion]]\n[[Category:1990s fashion]]\n[[Category:2000s fashion]]\n[[Category:2010s fashion]]\n[[Category:Polynesian words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Skin conditions resulting from physical factors]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "2402:3a80:828:62c6:c69c:d7e7:b292:7432", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I Have A Organization Tattoosideas & I Share 100000 ideas Of Tattoos.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tattoo"}
{"title_page": "Udo, Nigeria", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{tone|date=April 2016}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2016}}\n}}\n\n'''Udo''' is a populated area in Ezinihitte Mbaise, Imo State Nigeria.\n\n==History==\nUdo is not without folklore told to the people by their forefather and handed down from generation to generation. There are no written records stating the exact date their ancestors settled in the present location.  Be that as it may, those who were verse in oral history and generation age calculation estimated it to be over 1,500 years. \u201cUdoabia\u201d for short called Udo, meaning \"Peace has come in our Community\" and an ancient town located East of [[Ezinihitte-Mbaise|Ezinihitte Mbaise]] Local Government Area. The Community is situated at the shores of the [[Imo River]]. The Community shares border with Umunwanwa in [[Abia (state)|Abia State]] and [[Obowo]] in [[Imo (state)|Imo State]]. A rural agrarian and fishing community. Udo played host to early Christian Missionaries who settled by the river bank and traded in palm kernel.\n\nThe present traditional ruler, Eze M.C. Ukeje JP, Udoabia IV is one of the oldest and longest serving traditional rulers in the entire Imo State having ascended the throne in 1977. Udo is a community in Ezinihitte clan. Oral history traces the origin of Udo to Udoabia who was a direct son of Ezinihitte.\n\n==Migration==\n\nMany centuries ago Udoabia the progenitor of Udo Ancient Kingdom sojourned at the present Umuezeukwu Onicha briefly, Migrated and settled also at Eziama Onicha many years ago.\n\nUdoabia finally left Eziama Onicha and settled to its present location. This was estimated to be over 1,500 years ago.\n\nThis historical fact of Udoabia\u2019s sojourn at Eziama Onicha before his final settlement in this place called Udo, gave birth to cultural ceremony of ''Ibo Uzo Ukwu'' (meaning seasonal weeding of track road Udoabia took and returned to Udo from Onicha). The ceremony is performed every November 4. Once this ceremony is performed, no pledger will be permitted to redeem his land until the next farming year. This ceremony used to be centre of attraction in that it was rotatory between Udo and Eziama Onicha. On a yearly basis, one community will weed track up to the boundary of the other and mutatis-mutandis after which there will be elaborate merriment. There is this believe that Udoabia may have left Eziama behind at Onicha that explains why Udo and Eziama Onicha cannot intermarry. While it is true that Udo and Eziama cannot intermarry, it has not been proved with scientific or historical fact as to why they cannot intermarry or whether Eziama was left behind at Onicha. When Udo was returning, he came back with his two sons namely, [[Umuneorie]] and [[Umuofor]] while he begot [[Uhuala]] in Udo on return.\n\nEach of the three sons of Udo married and had children. The descendants of first son \u201cOrie\u201d multiplied in numbers to become Umuneorie which means children of Orie. Same applied to Ofo now called Umuofo and Uhuala. It is instructive to state that Ofo and Uhuola are of the same mother and this explains why Umuofor and Uhuala villages do not intermarry.\n\nThe name Udo originated from their ancient descendant and original ancestor called Udoabia. This explains why all the traditional rulers have as suffix to their names as title indicating a dynasty of UDOABIA. It is the three sons of Udo that formed the three villages and thirteen kindreds.\n\nFrom the inception of British Rule, particularly in the early 20th century, the successive traditional rulers of Udo have been recognized by government. These were Eze Onyewuchi Ogumba 1903-1925, Eze Uwalaka Nzerem 1925-1942, Chief Godwin Esonu 1944-1959 as a warrant Chief, Rev. Aaron Ezebugwu Ohaeri 1959-1976, who was elected head of Ezi Clan in 1960 to represent Ezi Clan in the Eastern House of Chiefs, Enugu, and the present Eze Eze (Dr.) Mathew Chukwuemeka Ukeje JP from 1976 till date. Eze M.C Ukeje has been on the throne for 38 years. He is one of the longest serving Eze in Imo State.\n\nUdo is one of the few Original Ancient Kingdoms that has not been fragmented.\n\nUdo has remained one indivisible and indissoluble autonomous Community under God in [[Ezinihitte-Mbaise|Ezinihitte]]. By implication the only community that has retained its originality as it was at creation at Orie-Ukwu. This is why it qualified to be called Ancient Kingdom. Udo is governed with constitution. Her population is about '''22,000'''\n\nThe community is blessed with [[Imo River]] and beautiful streams in all the villages which has provided a source of livelihood to the entire citizens. Most of the sand and gravel supplied to needing communities in [[Mbaise]] and beyond is excavated from the River. [[Hippopotamus]] or [[Enyimiri]] and fish are a common sea animal\u2019s people hunt and trade on.\n\nUdo is decorated with beautiful fauna and flora. The land in Udo is fertile which has made it possible for cultivation of different seasonal crops. The half proportion of the community is table land while some areas are erosion prone specially Uhuala and Umuneorie. These erosion, if not checked would cause menace to the lives of the inhabitants of these areas.\n\nThe main occupation of the people i.e. for the local populace is trading, farming, fishing.\n\n==Geography==\n\nThe Community which covers an area of approximately 20 square kilometers is situated west of the [[Imo River]], bounded on the East by Umunwanwa in [[Abia (state)|Abia State]], West by Obokwu/Obizi Communities in [[Ezinihitte-Mbaise|Ezinihitte Mbaise]] Local Government, on the South by [[Nsirimo]] also in [[Abia (state)|Abia State]] and on the North by Avutu in Obowo Local Government of [[Imo (state)|Imo State.]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/groups/205008180003103/|title=Udo Worldwide|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}\n\n{{coord missing|Nigeria}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Abia State]]\n", "text_old": "{{tone|date=April 2016}}\n{{more references|date=April 2016}}\n\n'''Udo''' is a populated area in Ezinihitte Mbaise, Imo State Nigeria.\n\n==History==\nUdo is not without folklore told to the people by their forefather and handed down from generation to generation. There are no written records stating the exact date their ancestors settled in the present location.  Be that as it may, those who were verse in oral history and generation age calculation estimated it to be over 1,500 years. \u201cUdoabia\u201d for short called Udo, meaning \"Peace has come in our Community\" and an ancient town located East of [[Ezinihitte-Mbaise|Ezinihitte Mbaise]] Local Government Area. The Community is situated at the shores of the [[Imo River]]. The Community shares border with Umunwanwa in [[Abia (state)|Abia State]] and [[Obowo]] in [[Imo (state)|Imo State]]. A rural agrarian and fishing community. Udo played host to early Christian Missionaries who settled by the river bank and traded in palm kernel. \n\nThe present traditional ruler, Eze M.C. Ukeje JP, Udoabia IV is one of the oldest and longest serving traditional rulers in the entire Imo State having ascended the throne in 1977. Udo is a community in Ezinihitte clan. Oral history traces the origin of Udo to Udoabia who was a direct son of Ezinihitte.\n\n==Migration==\n\nMany centuries ago Udoabia the progenitor of Udo Ancient Kingdom sojourned at the present Umuezeukwu Onicha briefly, Migrated and settled also at Eziama Onicha many years ago.\n\nUdoabia finally left Eziama Onicha and settled to its present location. This was estimated tobe over 1,500 years ago.\n\nThis historical fact of Udoabia\u2019s sojourn at Eziama Onicha before his final settlement in this place called Udo, gave birth to cultural ceremony of ''Ibo Uzo Ukwu'' (meaning seasonal weeding of track road Udoabia took and returned to Udo from Onicha). The ceremony is performed every November 4. Once this ceremony is performed, no pledger will be permitted to redeem his land until the next farming year. This ceremony used to be centre of attraction in that it was rotatory between Udo and Eziama Onicha. On a yearly basis, one community will weed track up to the boundary of the other and mutatis-mutandis after which there will be elaborate merriment. There is this believe that Udoabia may have left Eziama behind at Onicha that explains why Udo and Eziama Onicha cannot intermarry. While it is true that Udo and Eziama cannot intermarry, it has not been proved with scientific or historical fact as to why they cannot intermarry or whether Eziama was left behind at Onicha. When Udo was returning, he came back with his two sons namely, [[Umuneorie]] and [[Umuofor]] while he begot [[Uhuala]] in Udo on return.    \n\nEach of the three sons of Udo married and had children. The descendants of first son \u201cOrie\u201d multiplied in numbers to become Umuneorie which means children of Orie. Same applied to Ofo now called Umuofo and Uhuala. It is instructive to state that Ofo and Uhuola are of the same mother and this explains why Umuofor and Uhuala villages do not intermarry.\n\nThe name Udo originated from their ancient descendant and original ancestor called Udoabia. This explains why all the traditional rulers have as suffix to their names as title indicating a dynasty of UDOABIA. It is the three sons of Udo that formed the three villages and thirteen kindreds.\n\nFrom the inception of British Rule, particularly in the early 20th century, the successive traditional rulers of Udo have been recognized by government. These were Eze Onyewuchi Ogumba 1903-1925, Eze Uwalaka Nzerem 1925-1942, Chief Godwin Esonu 1944-1959 as a warrant Chief, Rev. Aaron Ezebugwu Ohaeri 1959-1976, who was elected head of Ezi Clan in 1960 to represent Ezi Clan in the Eastern House of Chiefs, Enugu, and the present Eze Eze (Dr.) Mathew Chukwuemeka Ukeje JP from 1976 till date. Eze M.C Ukeje has been on the throne for 38 years. He is one of the longest serving Eze in Imo State.\n\nUdo is one of the few Original Ancient Kingdoms that has not been fragmented.\n\nUdo has remained one indivisible and indissoluble autonomous Community under God in [[Ezinihitte-Mbaise|Ezinihitte]]. By implication the only community that has retained its originality as it was at creation at Orie-Ukwu. This is why it qualified to be called Ancient Kingdom. Udo is governed with constitution. Her population is about '''22,000''' \n\nThe community is blessed with [[Imo River]] and beautiful streams in all the villages which has provided a source of livelihood to the entire citizens. Most of the sand and gravel supplied to needing communities in [[Mbaise]] and beyond is excavated from the River. [[Hippopotamus]] or [[Enyimiri]] and fish are a common sea animal\u2019s people hunt and trade on.\n\nUdo is decorated with beautiful fauna and flora. The land in Udo is fertile which has made it possible for cultivation of different seasonal crops. The half proportion of the community is table land while some areas are erosion prone specially Uhuala and Umuneorie. These erosion, if not checked would cause menace to the lives of the inhabitants of these areas.\n\nThe main occupation of the people i.e. for the local populace is trading, farming, fishing.\n\n==Geography==\n\nThe Community which covers an area of approximately 20 square kilometers is situated west of the [[Imo River]], bounded on the East by Umunwanwa in [[Abia (state)|Abia State]], West by Obokwu/Obizi Communities in [[Ezinihitte-Mbaise|Ezinihitte Mbaise]] Local Government, on the South by [[Nsirimo]] also in [[Abia (state)|Abia State]] and on the North by Avutu in Obowo Local Government of [[Imo (state)|Imo State.]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/groups/205008180003103/|title=Udo Worldwide|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-09}}\n\n{{coord missing|Nigeria}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Abia State]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: tobe \u2192 to be", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Udo,_Nigeria"}
{"title_page": "Iberian lynx", "text_new": "{{Short description|Small wild cat}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Iberian lynx\n| taxon = Lynx pardinus\n| authority = ([[Coenraad Jacob Temminck|Temminck]], 1827)\n| status = EN\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{Cite iucn |title=''Lynx pardinus'' |author=Rodr\u00edguez, A. |author2=Calzada, J. |last-author-amp=yes |page=e.T12520A50655794 |date=2015 |access-date=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n| image = Lince Ib\u00e9rico Do\u00f1ana.jpg\n| range_map = IberianLynx distribution2015.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Distribution of Iberian Lynx, 2015\n| fossil_range=[[Early Pleistocene]]<ref name=Boscaini_al2016>{{cite journal |author1=Boscaini, A. |last-author-amp=yes |author2=Alba, D.M. |author3=Beltr\u00e1n, J.F. |author4=Moya-Sola, S. |author5=Madurell-Malapeira, J. |year=2016 |title=Latest Early Pleistocene remains of ''Lynx pardinus'' (Carnivora, Felidae) from the Iberian Peninsula: taxonomy and evolutionary implications |journal=Quaternary Science Reviews |volume=143 |issue= |pages=96\u2013106 |doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2016.05.015 |url=}}</ref>-Recent {{Geological range|1.7|0}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Iberian lynx''' (''Lynx pardinus'') is a wild [[Felidae|cat]] [[Species (biological)|species]] [[endemic]] to the [[Iberian Peninsula]] in southwestern Europe. It is listed as [[endangered species|Endangered]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=iucn /> In the 20th century, the Iberian lynx population had declined because of overhunting and [[poaching]], fragmentation of suitable habitats; the population of its main prey species, the [[European rabbit]] (''Oryctolagus cuniculus''), experienced a severe decline caused by [[myxomatosis]] and [[rabbit haemorrhagic disease]].<ref name=Sim\u00f3n2012>{{cite book |author=Sim\u00f3n, M.A. |year=2012 |title=Ten years conserving the Iberian lynx |publisher=Consejer\u00eda de Agricultura, Pesca y Medio Ambiente. Junta de Andalus\u00eda |location=Seville |isbn=9788492807802|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VhFEETrncwEC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rodr\u00edguez-Hidalgo |first1=A. |last2=Lloveras |first2=L. |last3=Moreno-Garc\u00eda |first3=M. |last4=Saladi\u00e9 |first4=P. |last5=Canals |first5=A. |last6=Nadal |first6=J. |year=2013 |title=Feeding behaviour and taphonomic characterization of non-ingested rabbit remains produced by the Iberian lynx (''Lynx pardinus'') |journal=Journal of Archaeological Science |volume=40 |issue=7 |pages=3031\u20133045 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/236208653 |doi=10.1016/j.jas.2013.03.006 |hdl=10261/153608}}</ref><ref name=Fordham2013>{{cite journal |last1=Fordham |first1=D.A. |last2=Ak\u00e7akaya |first2=H.R. |last3=Brook |first3=B.W. |last4=Rodr\u00edguez |first4=A. |last5=Alves |first5=P.C. |last6=Civantos |first6=E. |last7=Trivino |first7=M. |last8=Watts |first8=M.J. |last9=Araujo |first9=M.B. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2013 |title=Adapted conservation measures are required to save the Iberian lynx in a changing climate |journal=Nature Climate Change |volume=3 |issue=10 |pages=899\u2013903 |bibcode=2013NatCC...3..899F |hdl=10261/84387 |doi=10.1038/nclimate1954 |url=http://digital.csic.es/bitstream/10261/84387/1/Fordham_Nat%20Clim%20Change_13.pdf}}</ref>\n\nBy the turn of the 21st century, the Iberian lynx was on the verge of extinction, as only about 100 individuals survived in two isolated subpopulations in [[Andalusia]]. Conservation measures were implemented since 2002 which included improving habitat, restocking of rabbits, [[Translocation (wildlife conservation)|translocating]],  [[Species reintroduction|re-introducing]] and monitoring Iberian lynxes. By 2012, the population had increased to 326 individuals.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lopez |first1=G. |last2=Lopez |first2=M. |last3=Fernandez |first3=L. |last4=Ruiz |first4=G. |last5=Arenas|first5=R. |last6=Del Rey |first6=T. |last7=Gil |first7=J.M. |last8=Garrote |first8=G. |last9=Garcia |first9=M. |last10=Simon |first10=M. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2012 |title=Population development of the Iberian lynx since 2002 |journal=Cat News |volume=57 |page=34}}</ref>\n\nIt is a [[monotypic]] species and is thought to have evolved from ''[[Lynx issiodorensis]]''.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n''Felis pardina'' was the [[scientific name]] proposed by [[Coenraad Jacob Temminck]] in 1827 who described skins of Iberian lynxes that were killed in the area of the [[Tagus]] river in Portugal and were traded in Paris and London.<ref>{{cite book |last=Temminck, C. J. |year=1827 |title=Monographies de mammalogie, ou description de quelques genres de mammif\u00e8res, dont les esp\u00e8ces ont \u00e9t\u00e9 observ\u00e9es dans les diff\u00e9rens mus\u00e9es de l'Europe. Vol. 1 |location=Leiden |publisher=C. C. Vander Hoek |chapter=''Felis pardina'' |pages=116\u2212117 |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/monographiedema00temm/page/116}}</ref>\nIt is a [[monotypic]] species.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten, C. |author3=Eizirik, E. |author4=Gentry, A. |author5=Werdelin, L. |author6=Wilting, A. |author7=Yamaguchi, N. |author8=Abramov, A. V. |author9=Christiansen, P. |author10=Driscoll, C. |author11=Duckworth, J. W. |author12=Johnson, W. |author13=Luo, S.-J. |author14=Meijaard, E. |author15=O\u2019Donoghue, P. |author16=Sanderson, J. |author17=Seymour, K. |author18=Bruford, M. |author19=Groves, C. |author20=Hoffmann, M. |author21=Nowell, K. |author22=Timmons, Z. |author23=Tobe, S. |year=2017 |title=A revised taxonomy of the Felidae: The final report of the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group |journal=Cat News |volume=Special Issue 11 |pages=45 |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/32616/A_revised_Felidae_Taxonomy_CatNews.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y#page=45}}</ref>\n\n=== Evolution ===\nThe Iberian lynx is thought to have evolved from ''[[Lynx issiodorensis]]''.<ref name=pmoe68>{{cite book |first= B. |last= Kurt\u00e9n |title=Pleistocene Mammals of Europe |year=1968 |publisher=Aldine Transaction |location=London, New Brunswick}}</ref>\nThe earliest [[fossil]] remains of the Iberian lynx date to the [[Early Pleistocene]].<ref name=Boscaini_al2016/>\n\n== Characteristics ==\nThe Iberian lynx has a short bright yellowish to tawny coloured spotted fur. The spots vary in shape and size from small round to elongate. They are arranged in lines and decrease in size from the back towards the sides.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Beltr\u00e1n |first1=J.F. |last2=Delibes |first2=M. |year=1993 |title=Physical characteristics of Iberian lynxes (''Lynx pardinus'') from Do\u00f1ana, southwestern Spain |journal=Journal of Mammalogy |volume=74 |issue=4 |pages=852\u2013862 |doi=10.2307/1382423 |jstor=1382423}}</ref>\nIts head is small with tufted ears and a ruff. Its body is short with long legs and a short tail. Head and body length of males is {{convert|74.7-82|cm|abbr=on}} with a {{convert|12.5-16|cm|abbr=on}} long tail and a weight of {{convert|7-15.9|kg|abbr=on}}. Females are smaller with a head-to-body-length of approximately {{convert|68.2-77.5|cm|abbr=on}} and a weight of {{convert|9.2-10|kg|abbr=on}}.<ref name=WCoW>{{cite book |first=M. |last=Sunquist |first2=F. |last2=Sunquist |last-author-amp=yes |year=2002 |title=Wild cats of the World |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago |isbn=978-0-226-77999-7 |chapter=Iberian Lynx ''Lynx pardinus'' (Temminck, 1827) |pages=177\u2013184 |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/wildcatsofworld00sunq/page/177}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\nThe Iberian lynx was once present throughout the Iberian Peninsula and southern France. In the 1950s, the northern population extended from the [[Mediterranean]] to [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] and parts of northern Portugal, and the southern population from central to southern Spain.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Clavero |first1=M. |last2=Delibes |first2=M. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2013 |title=Using historical accounts to set conservation baselines: the case of Lynx species in Spain |journal=Biodiversity and Conservation |volume=22 |issue=8 |pages=1691\u20131702 |doi=10.1007/s10531-013-0506-4 |hdl=10261/80444|hdl-access=free }}</ref> Populations declined from 15 subpopulations in the 1940s to only two subpopulations in the early 1990s, most noticeably in [[Montes de Toledo]] and [[Sierra Morena]]. Before 1973, it was present in [[Sierra de Gata]], Montes de Toledo, eastern Sierra Morena, Sierra de Relumbrar and coastal plains in the Do\u00f1ana area. Between the early 1960s and 2000, it has lost about 80% of its former range.<ref name=AC2008>{{cite journal |last1=Alda |first1=F. |last2=Inog\u00e9s |first2=J. |last3=Alcaraz |first3=L. |last4=Oria |first4=J. |last5=Aranda |first5=A. |last6=Doadrio |first6=I. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2008 |title=Looking for the Iberian lynx in central Spain: a needle in a hay stack? |journal=Animal Conservation |volume=11 |issue=4 |pages=297\u2013305 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2008.00185.x}}</ref><ref name=JM2011>{{cite journal |last1=Gil-Sanchez |first1=J.M. |last2=McCain |first2=E.B. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2011 |title=Former range and decline of the Iberian lynx (''Lynx pardinus'') reconstructed using verified records |journal=Journal of Mammalogy |volume=92 |issue=5 |pages=1081\u20131090 |doi=10.1644/10-MAMM-A-381.1|doi-access=free }}</ref> It is now restricted to very limited areas in southern Spain, with breeding only confirmed in Sierra Morena and Do\u00f1ana coastal plains.<ref name=Sim\u00f3n2012/>\n\n[[Fossil]] remains indicate that the Iberian lynx had a wider range during the [[Late Pleistocene]] and [[Holocene]]. Five lynx remains found in [[Arene Candide]] in northern Italy date to about 24,820\u201318,620 [[before present]]. One specimen found in Cabias cave in southern France was [[radiocarbon date]]d to 3780\u00b190 before present.<ref name=QSR150315>{{cite journal |title=Ancient DNA evidence of Iberian lynx palaeoendemism |journal=Quaternary Science Reviews |volume=112 |pages=172\u2013180 |date=2015 |doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2015.01.009 |last1=Rodr\u00edguez-Varela |first1=R. |last2=Tagliacozzo |first2=A. |last3=Ure\u00f1a |first3=I. |last4=Garc\u00eda |first4=N. |last5=Cr\u00e9gut-Bonnoure |first5=E. |last6=Mannino |first6=M. A. |last7=Arsuaga |first7=J. L. |last8=Valdiosera |first8=C. |last-author-amp=yes |bibcode=2015QSRv..112..172R |url= }}</ref>\n\nThe Iberian lynx prefers [[heterogeneous]] environments of open grassland mixed with dense shrubs such as [[Arbutus unedo|strawberry tree]], [[Pistacia lentiscus|mastic]], and [[juniper]], and trees such as [[holm oak]] and [[cork oak]]. It is now largely restricted to mountainous areas.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\nThe Iberian lynx [[Spraying (animal behavior)|marks its territory with its urine]], scratch marks on the barks of trees, and scat. The home ranges of adults are stable over many years.<ref name=WCoW />\nCamera trapping surveys in the eastern Sierra Morena Mountains between 1999 and 2008 revealed that six females had home ranges of {{convert|5.2-6.6|km2|abbr=on}}. Four males in the area had home ranges of {{convert|11.8-12.2|km2|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Gil-S\u00e1nchez, J.M. |last-author-amp=yes |author2=Moral, M. |author3=Bueno, J. |author4=Rodr\u00edguez-Siles, J. |author5=Lillo, S. |author6=P\u00e9rez, J. |author7=Mart\u00edn, J.M. |author8=Valenzuela, G. |author9=Garrote, G. |author10=Torralba, B. |author11=Sim\u00f3n-Mata, M.\u00c1. |year=2011 |title=The use of camera trapping for estimating Iberian lynx (''Lynx pardinus'') home ranges |journal=European Journal of Wildlife Research |volume=57 |issue=6 |pages=1203\u20131211 |doi=10.1007/s10344-011-0533-y |citeseerx=10.1.1.459.5581 }}</ref>\n\n=== Diet and hunting ===\n{{Multiple image |direction=vertical |align=top |header=Iberian lynx hunting [[common quail]] (''Coturnix coturnix'')\n|image1=Iberian Lynx catching his prey.jpg |caption1=Swiping with right paw with claws extended\n|image2=Iberian Lynx eating bird.jpg |caption2=Caught prey in mouth}}\nThe Iberian lynx preys foremost on the [[European rabbit]] (''Oryctolagus cuniculus'') for the bulk of its diet, supplemented by [[red-legged partridge]] (''Alectoris rufa''), [[rodent]]s and to a smaller degree also on wild [[ungulate]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Palomares  |first1=F. |last2=Delibes |first2=M. |last3=Revilla |first3=E. |last4=Calzada |first4=J. |last5=Frediani |first5=J.M. |year=2001 |title=Spatial ecology of Iberian lynx and abundance of European rabbits in south-western Spain |jstor=3830752 |journal=Wildlife Monographs |volume=148 |issue=148 |pages=1\u201336}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gil-S\u00e1nchez |first1=J.M. |last2=Ballesteros-Duper\u00f3n |first2=E. |last3=Bueno-Segura |first3=J.F. |year=2006 |title=Feeding ecology of the Iberian lynx ''Lynx pardinus'' in eastern Sierra Morena (Southern Spain) |journal=Acta Theriologica |volume= 51 |pages= 85\u201390 |doi=10.1007/bf03192659}}</ref><ref name=LopezBao2011>{{cite journal |last1=L\u00f3pez\u2010Bao |first1=J.V. |last2=Palomares |first2=F. |last3=Rodr\u00edguez |first3=A. |last4=Ferreras |first4=P. |title=Intraspecific interference influences the use of prey hotspots |journal=Oikos |volume=120 |issue=10 |year=2011 |pages=1489\u20131496 |doi= 10.1111/j.1600-0706.2011.19194.x |hdl=10261/39785|hdl-access=free }}</ref>\nIt sometimes preys on young [[fallow deer]] (''Dama dama''), [[roe deer]] (''Capreolus capreolus''), [[mouflon]] (''Ovis orientalis''), and ducks.<ref name=DelibesRod2000>{{cite book |last=Delibes |first=A. |last2=Rodr\u00edguez |first2=M. |last3=Ferreras |first3=P. |title=Action Plan for the Conservation of the Iberian Lynx in Europe (''Lynx pardinus'') |date=2000 |publisher=Council of Europe |isbn=978-92-871-4423-2 |url=http://digital.csic.es/bitstream/10261/59779/1/SN111-E.pdf}}</ref> A male requires one rabbit per day while a female raising kittens will eat three per day.<ref name=ward>{{cite book |url=http://wardenvironment.ch/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Ward_REP_The_Iberian_lynx_emergency.pdf |first=D. |last=Ward |title=The Iberian Lynx Emergency |year=2004 |publisher=EU commissioned report}}</ref>\n\nThe Iberian species has low adaptability\u2014it continued to rely heavily on rabbits (75% of its food intake) despite the latter's repeated population crashes due to [[myxomatosis]] and [[rabbit haemorrhagic disease]].<ref name=Fordham2013/>\n\nIt competes for prey with [[red fox]] (''Vulpes vulpes''), [[Egyptian mongoose]] (''Herpestes ichneumon'') and [[European wildcat]] (''Felis silvestris''). Also, it often kills other smaller carnivores such as red fox, Egyptian mongoose and [[common genet]] (''Genetta genetta'').<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fedriani |first1=J. M. |last2=Palomares |first2=F. |last3=Delibes |first3=M. |year=1999 |title=Niche relations among three sympatric Mediterranean carnivores |url= |journal=Oecologia |volume=121 |issue=1 |pages=138\u2013148 |doi=10.1007/s004420050915 |pmid=28307883 |bibcode=1999Oecol.121..138F |citeseerx=10.1.1.587.7215}}</ref> The species is solitary and hunts alone; it will stalk its prey or lie in wait for hours behind a bush or rock until the prey is sufficiently close to pounce in a few strides.\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n[[File:Iberian_Lynx_cub_07.jpg|thumb|Iberian lynx cub]]\nDuring the mating season the female leaves her territory in search of a male. The typical [[gestation]] period is about two months; the kittens are born between March and September, with a peak of births in March and April. A litter consists of two or three (rarely one, four or five) kittens weighing between {{convert|200|and|250|g|oz}}.\n\nThe kittens become independent at 7 to 10 months old, but remain with the mother until around 20 months old. Survival of the young depends heavily on the availability of prey species. In the wild, both males and females reach sexual maturity at the age of one year, though in practice they rarely breed until a territory becomes vacant; one female was known not to breed until five years old when its mother died. The maximum longevity in the wild is 13 years.<ref name=iucncsg>{{cite web |url= http://lynx.uio.no/jon/lynx/lynxib01.htm |title= Iberian lynx ''Lynx pardinus'' |publisher= IUCN Cat Specialist Group |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110724185701/http://lynx.uio.no/jon/lynx/lynxib01.htm |archive-date= 24 July 2011 |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=adw>{{cite web |url= http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Lynx_pardinus.html |title= ''Lynx pardinus'' |publisher= Animal Diversity Web }}</ref>\n\nSiblings become violent towards one another between 30 and 60 days, peaking at 45 days. A kitten will frequently kill its littermate in a brutal fight. It is unknown why these episodes of aggression occur, though many scientists believe it is related to a change in hormones when a kitten switches from its mother's milk to meat. Others believe it is related to hierarchy, and \"[[survival of the fittest]]\".\n\nDifficulty in finding mates has led to more inbreeding, which results in fewer kittens and a greater rate of non-traumatic death.<ref name=EJWR2012>{{cite journal |first=F. |last=Palomares |first2=J. A. |last2=Godoy |first3=J. V. |last3=Lopez-Bao |title=Possible Extinction Vortex for a Population of Iberian Lynx on the Verge of Extirpation |journal=Conservation Biology |volume=26 |issue=4 |pages=689\u2013697 |year=2012 |doi=10.1111/j.1523-1739.2012.01870.x |pmid= 22731698 |hdl=10261/55052|hdl-access=free }}</ref> Inbreeding leads to lower semen quality and greater rates of infertility in males, hindering efforts to increase the species' fitness.<ref name=CB2013>{{cite journal |first=M. J. |last=Ruiz-Lopez |first2=N. |last2=Ganan |first3=J. A. |last3=Godoy |title=Heterozygosity-Fitness Correlations and Inbreeding Depression in two Critically Endangered Mammals |journal=Conservation Biology |volume=26 |issue=1 |pages=1121\u20131129 |year=2013 |doi=10.1111/j.1523-1739.2012.01916.x |pmid=22897325 |hdl=10261/63937}}</ref>\n\n== Threats ==\nThe Iberian lynx is threatened by habitat loss, road accidents and illegal hunting.<ref name=iucn/> Habitat loss is due mainly to infrastructure improvement, urban and resort development and tree mono cultivation, which fragments the lynx's distribution. In the 20th century, rabbit diseases such as [[myxomatosis]] and [[Rabbit haemorrhagic disease|hemorrhagic disease]] resulted in a dramatic decline of its main prey.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Ecosystem Effects of Variant Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease Virus, Iberian Peninsula |first1=M. |last1=Delibes-Mateos |first2=C. |last2=Ferreira |first3=F. |last3=Carro |first4=M. A. |last4=Escudero |first5=C. |last5=Gort\u00e1zar |last-author-amp=yes |journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases |volume=20 |issue=12 |pages=2166\u20132168 |year=2014 |doi=10.3201/eid2012.140517 |pmid=25417710 |pmc=4257825}}</ref> Illegal traps set for rabbits and foxes were leading causes for lynx fatality in the 1990s.<ref name=BC1992>{{cite journal |last1=Ferreras |first1=P. |last2=Aldama |first2=J.J. |last3=Beltran |first3=J. |last4=Delibes |first4=M. |last-author-amp=yes |year=1992 |title=Rates and causes of mortality in a fragmented population of Iberian lynx ''Felis pardina'' Temminck, 1824 |url= |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=62 |issue=3 |pages=197\u2013202 |doi=10.1016/0006-3207(92)91116-a |hdl=10261/50936|hdl-access=free }}</ref>\nEvery year, several Iberian lynxes die when trying to cross highways with heavy traffic.<ref name=Sim\u00f3n2012/> In 2013, 14 Iberian lynxes died on roads, and 21 in 2014.<ref name=EFE140101>{{cite news |url=http://www.andalucesdiario.es/provincias/huelva/el-atropello-mortal-de-14-linces-en-2013-merma-la-recuperacion-de-la-especie/ |title=El atropello mortal de 14 linces en 2013 merma la recuperaci\u00f3n de la especie |language=Spanish |trans-title=14 lynxes were fatally run over in 2013, undermining the species' recovery |newspaper=Andaluces Diario |date=2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106081726/http://www.andalucesdiario.es/provincias/huelva/el-atropello-mortal-de-14-linces-en-2013-merma-la-recuperacion-de-la-especie/ |archive-date=6 January 2014 |url-status=dead |access-date=6 January 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Pais150219>{{cite news |url= http://elpais.com/elpais/2015/02/16/inenglish/1424097857_034701.html |title=Rise in Iberian lynx road deaths speeds up protection plans |first=G. |last=Donaire |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |date=2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, several individuals died of [[feline leukemia]].<ref>{{cite journal |author1=L\u00f3pez, G. |last-author-amp=yes |author2=L\u00f3pez-Parra, M. |author3=Fern\u00e1ndez, L. |author4=Mart\u00ednez-Granados, C. |author5=Mart\u00ednez, F. |author6=Meli, M.L. |author7=Gil-S\u00e1nchez, J.M. |author8=Viqueira, N. |author9=D\u00edaz-Portero, M.A. |author10=Cadenas, R. |author11=Lutz, H. |author12=Vargas, A. |author13=Sim\u00f3n, M.A. |year=2009 |title=Management measures to control a feline leukemia virus outbreak in the endangered Iberian lynx |journal=Animal Conservation |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=173\u2013182 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2009.00241.x }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Palomares, F. |last-author-amp=yes |author2=L\u00f3pez-Bao, J.V. |author3=Rodr\u00edguez, A. |year=2011 |title=Feline leukaemia virus outbreak in the endangered Iberian lynx and the role of feeding stations: a cautionary tale |journal=Animal Conservation |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=242\u2013245 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2010.00403.x|hdl=10261/39812 |hdl-access=free }}</ref>  \n\nIn 2013, it was reported that the Iberian lynx possesses antibiotic resistant bacteria within its digestive tract, which may lead to more dangerous and difficult-to-treat infections and decrease the cat's fitness.<ref>{{cite journal |first=A. |last=Gon\u00e7alves |first2=G. |last2=Igrejas |first3=T. |last3=Hajer |last-author-amp=yes |title=Detection of antibiotic resistant enterococci and ''Escherichia coli'' in free range Iberian Lynx (''Lynx pardinus'') |journal=Science of the Total Environment |volume=456\u2013457 |pages=115\u2013119 |year=2013 |doi=10.1016/j.scitotenv.2013.03.073 |pmid=23588135 |bibcode=2013ScTEn.456..115G}}</ref> A 2013 study suggests climate change may threaten the Iberian lynx species due to their inability to adapt well to a climate change or it may lead them to relocate to areas that have a more suitable climate but fewer rabbits, increasing mortality.<ref name=Fordham2013/>\n\n== Conservation ==\n[[File:Linces10.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Iberian lynx]]\nThe Iberian lynx is fully protected. It is listed on [[CITES Appendix I]], on Appendix II of the [[Berne Convention on the Conservation of European Wildlife and Natural Habitats]] and on Annexes II and IV of the [[Habitats Directive]] of the [[European Union]]. It has been listed as Endangered on the IUCN Red List since 2014.<ref name=iucn />\n\nConservation measures include restoring its native habitat, maintaining the wild rabbit population, reducing unnatural causes of death, and releasing captive bred individuals.<ref name=Vargas2008>{{cite journal |authors=Vargas, A., S\u00e1nchez, I., Mart\u00ednez, F., Rivas, A., Godoy, J.A., Roldan, E., Sim\u00f3n, M.A., Serra, R., Perez, M.A.J., Ensenat, C. and Delibes, M. |year=2008 |title=The Iberian lynx ''Lynx pardinus'' Conservation Breeding Program |journal=International Zoo Yearbook |volume=42 |pages=190\u2013198 |doi=10.1111/j.1748-1090.2007.00036.x |hdl=10261/50244 |url=http://digital.csic.es/bitstream/10261/50244/3/105225.pdf}}</ref> \nThe Spanish National Commission for the Protection of Nature endorsed the Iberian Lynx Ex Situ Conservation Breeding Program to serve as a \"safety net\" by managing the captive population and also to \"help establish new Iberian lynx free-ranging populations through reintroduction programmes.\" Before release of captive-bred cats, their natural habit may be simulated to prepare them for life in the wild.<ref name=Vargas2008 /> A 2006 study used a non-intrusive monitoring system involving cameras to monitor the demographics of both lynxes and rabbits residing in Sierra Morena. Supplemental food sources could be provided if wild rabbits suffered a decline.<ref name=GilSanchez2010>{{cite journal |first=J. |last=Gil-S\u00e1nchez |first2=M. |last2=Sim\u00f3n |first3=R. |last3=Cadenas |first4=J. |last4=Bueno |first5=M. |last5=Moral |first6=J. |last6=Rodr\u00edguez-Siles |year=2010 |title=Current Status Of the Iberian Lynx (''Lynx pardinus'') in eastern Sierra Morena, Southern Spain |journal=Wildlife Biology in Practice |volume=6 |issue=3 |pages=14\u201333 |doi=10.2461/wbp.lynx.2 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/228505844}}</ref>\n\nManagement efforts are being developed to conserve and restore the animal's native range.<ref name=Clavero2013>{{cite journal |last1=Clavero |first1=M. |last2=Delibes |first2=M. |year=2013 |title=Using historical accounts to set conservation baselines: the case of Lynx species in Spain |journal=Biodiversity Conservation Journal |volume=22 |issue=8 |pages=1691\u20131702 |doi=10.1007/s10531-013-0506-4|hdl=10261/80444|hdl-access=free }}</ref> Officials intending to release captive-bred lynx look for areas of appropriate habitat, rabbit abundance, and acceptance by the local human population.<ref name=NL130621>{{cite news |url= https://naturlink.sapo.pt/Noticias/Noticias/content/Lince-iberico-Jazz-e-Joaninha-que-nasceram-em-Silves-em-2012-foram-hoje-libertados-na-Andaluzia?bl=1 |title=Lince-ib\u00e9rico: Jazz e Joaninha, que nasceram em Silves em 2012, foram hoje libertados na Andaluzia |language= Portuguese |trans-title= Iberian lynx: Jazz and Joaninha, who were born in Silves in 2012, were released today in Andalusia |first= F. |last= Alves |work= Naturlink |date= 21 June 2013 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130630230952/http://naturlink.sapo.pt/Noticias/Noticias/content/Lince-iberico-Jazz-e-Joaninha-que-nasceram-em-Silves-em-2012-foram-hoje-libertados-na-Andaluzia?bl=1 |archive-date= 30 June 2013 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> About 90 million euros was spent on various conservation measures between 1994 and 2013.<ref name=UA130722>{{cite news |url= http://www.adelaide.edu.au/news/news63241.html |title= Iberian lynx threatened by climate change |publisher= The University of Adelaide |date= 22 July 2013 }}</ref> The [[European Union]] contributes up to 61% of funding.<ref name=elpais131215>{{cite news |url= http://elpais.com/elpais/2013/12/15/inenglish/1387110752_809462.html |title= Iberian lynx faces new threat as disease decimates rabbit population |first= J. |last= Vi\u00fadez |work= El Pais |date= 15 December 2013 }}</ref><ref name=efe091003>{{cite news |url= http://www.abc.es/hemeroteca/historico-03-10-2009/abc/Sociedad/el-lince-iberico-inicia-una-incierta-reconquista_103358912739.html |title= El lince ib\u00e9rico inicia una incierta <<reconquista>> |language= Spanish |trans-title=The Iberian lynx begins an uncertain \"reconquest\" |work= EFE |publisher= ABC.es |date=2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Reintroduction programme ===\n[[File:Poblaci\u00f3n lince.jpg|thumb|Graph showing Iberian lynx population in Spain, 1960\u20132007]]\nBeginning in 2009, the Iberian lynx was reintroduced into [[Embalse de Guadalmellato|Guadalmellato]], resulting in a population of 23 in 2013.<ref name=eleco130408>{{cite news |url= http://ecodiario.eleconomista.es/espana/noticias/4730656/04/13/la-junta-de-andalucia-refuerza-en-el-guadalmellato-la-poblacion-de-lince-iberico-con-la-suelta-de-dos-ejemplares.html |title= La Junta de Andaluc\u00eda refuerza en el Guadalmellato la poblaci\u00f3n de lince ib\u00e9rico con la suelta de dos ejemplares |language= Spanish |trans-title=Andalusia reinforces Iberian lynx population in Guadalmellato with the release of two individuals |work= El Economista |date= 8 April 2013 }}</ref> Since 2010, the species has also been released in Guarrizas.<ref name=NL130621 /><ref name=decpaper>{{cite web |url= http://www.iberianature.com/material/documents/LynxBrief12E.pdf |title= LynxBrief |last=Ward |first= D. |date=2008}}</ref> Discussions were held with the Ministry of Environment on plans for releases in the Campanarios de Azaba area near [[Salamanca]].<ref name=rewild>{{cite web |url=http://rewildingeurope.com/news/articles/wildlife-returns-to-western-iberia/ |title=Wildlife returns to Western Iberia |publisher=Rewilding Europe |date=2012}}</ref> In April 2013, it was reported that Andalusia's total wild population\u2014only 94 in 2002\u2014had tripled to 309 individuals.<ref name=elmundo130409>{{cite news |url= http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2013/04/08/andalucia/1365443569.html |title=La poblaci\u00f3n de linces se triplica en Andaluc\u00eda en los \u00faltimos diez a\u00f1os |language= Spanish |trans-title=The lynx population has tripled in Andalusia in the last ten years |newspaper=El Mundo |date=2013}}</ref><ref name=eleco130408 /> In July 2013, environmental groups confirmed the presence of a wild-born litter in the [[Province of C\u00e1ceres]] ([[Extremadura]]).<ref name=efe130706>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.es/agencias/noticia.asp?noticia=1453396 |title= Grupos ecologistas confirman que el lince ib\u00e9rico cr\u00eda en libertad en C\u00e1ceres |language= Spanish |trans-title=Environmental group confirm the Iberian lynx is breeding in the wild in C\u00e1ceres |work= [[EFE]] |publisher= ABC.es |date=2013}}</ref> A study published in July 2013 in ''Nature Climate Change'' advised that reintroduction programs take place in northern Iberia, suggesting that climate change would threaten rabbits in the south.<ref name=UA130722 /><ref name=LS130721>{{cite news |url= http://www.livescience.com/38330-climate-change-iberian-lynx-extinction.html |title= Climate Change Could Wipe Out Iberian Lynx |first= Tia |last= Ghose |publisher= Live Science |date=2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 November 2014, 8 Iberian lynxes were released into [[Toledo, Spain]]; one of them traveled near [[Madrid]], the first time in 40 years.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://elpais.com/elpais/2015/03/09/inenglish/1425900807_150674.html|title= Iberian Lynx returns to Madrid region after 40 years|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 10 March 2015|website= |publisher= El Pais}}</ref>\n\nThe presence of Iberian lynxes in Portugal, particularly in the south, has been verified.<ref name=pu130601>{{cite news |url= http://www.publico.pt/n1596143 |title= Lince ib\u00e9rico, o mais amea\u00e7ado dos felinos, fotografado em Milfontes |language= Portuguese |trans-title=The Iberian Lynx, the most threatened feline, was photographed in Milfontes |first= M. |last=Soares |work=Publico.pt |date=2013}}</ref> In 2014, the [[Institute for Nature Conservation and Forests]] signed contracts securing 2,000 hectares of land for Portugal's reintroduction project.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lynx pardinas (2000)|url=http://www.icnf.pt/portal/naturaclas/rn2000/resource/docs/rn-plan-set/mamif/lynx-pardinus/|website=ICNF Portal|publisher=ICN:B|accessdate=27 June 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>[http://www.icnf.pt/portal/naturaclas/rn2000/resource/docs/rn-plan-set/mamif/lynx-pardinus/ ''Lynx pardinus'']. Instituto da Conserva\u00e7\u00e3o da Natureza e das Florestas, Portugal</ref><ref name=PN141113>{{cite news |url= http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/more-space-in-portugal-in-pipeline-for-iberian-lynx/33215 |title= More space in Portugal in pipeline for Iberian Lynx |first= Carrie-Marie |last= Bratley |work= The Portugal News |date= 13 November 2014 |access-date= 8 December 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141208113934/http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/more-space-in-portugal-in-pipeline-for-iberian-lynx/33215 |archive-date= 8 December 2014 |url-status= dead }}</ref> On 16 December 2014, a pair of Iberian lynx was released into [[Guadiana Valley Natural Park]] near [[M\u00e9rtola]], Portugal.<ref name=PN141218>{{cite news |url= http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/portugal-makes-history-with-first-release-of-iberian-lynx/33484 |title=Portugal makes history with first release of Iberian Lynx |work= The Portugal News |date= 18 December 2014}}</ref>\nOn 7 February 2015, another pair was released into the park, but the female was later found dead on 12 March 2015 after being poisoned in M\u00e9rtola.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/iberian-lynx-female-released-last-month-found-dead/34313|title= Iberian Lynx female released last month found dead|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 19 March 2015|website= |publisher= The Portugal News}}</ref> The last pair of captive-bred Iberian lynxes were released into Guadiana Valley Nature Reserve on 12 May 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/final-two-iberian-lynx-released-into-the-wild/34765|title= Final two Iberian Lynx released into the wild|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 14 May 2015|website= theportugalnews.com|publisher= The Portugal News}}</ref> By the end of 2015 there were 400 lynx on the Iberian peninsula, the vast majority in Andalusia, in southern Spain, but with smaller new populations in the hills near Toledo, in Extremadura (south-western Spain) and in southern Portugal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-35890789|title=The return of the lynx|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=28 March 2016|website=bbc.com|publisher=BBC|access-date=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe reintroduction of Iberian lynx in Portugal has been a success; from 17 animals that were reintroduced, 12 have already established territories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wilder.pt/historias/comecou-hoje-a-epoca-de-2017-de-libertacoes-de-linces-em-portugal/|title=Come\u00e7ou a \u00e9poca de 2017 de liberta\u00e7\u00f5es de linces em Portugal|date=17 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nSince a 2007 outbreak of [[feline leukemia virus]] (FeLV), wild lynxes are tested periodically for possible disease. September\u2013December 2013 samples were negative for FeLV but one male became the first of his species to test positive for [[feline immunodeficiency virus]] (FIV) and was placed into quarantine.<ref name=EP131230>{{cite news |url= http://noticias.lainformacion.com/salud/vacunas/resultado-negativo-en-los-chequeos-a-linces-para-detectar-leucemia-felina-con-un-positivo-de-virus-de-inmunodeficiencia_R1VgBI0UVEw0VXpuAsbjm7/ |title= Resultado negativo en los chequeos a linces para detectar leucemia felina, con un positivo de virus de inmunodeficiencia |language= Spanish |trans-title=Lynxes negative for feline leukemia but one positive for immunodeficiency virus |work= Europa Press |publisher= La Informacion |date=2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131231083837/http://noticias.lainformacion.com/salud/vacunas/resultado-negativo-en-los-chequeos-a-linces-para-detectar-leucemia-felina-con-un-positivo-de-virus-de-inmunodeficiencia_R1VgBI0UVEw0VXpuAsbjm7/ |archive-date= 31 December 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n=== Captive breeding ===\n[[File:Iberian Lynx CNRLI reproduction centre 10 May 2015 (15).JPG|thumb|The Iberian Lynx CNRLI reproduction centre near the village of Vale Fuzeiros (mun. of [[Silves, Portugal]])]]\nIn 2002, the Jerez Zoo confirmed it had three females and was developing a plan for a captive breeding program. One of those females was [[Saliega]], captured as a kitten in April 2002.<ref name=guard0204>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/apr/21/highereducation.biologicalscience |title= Captured cubs hold future of Europe's tiger |publisher= The Guardian |date= April 2002 |location=London |first=E. |last=Gon\u00e7alves}}</ref> She became the first Iberian lynx to breed in captivity, giving birth to three healthy kittens on 29 March 2005 at the El Acebuche Breeding Center, in the Do\u00f1ana Nature Park in [[Huelva]], Spain.<ref name=bbc050330>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/4394005.stm |work=BBC News |title=Hopes raised by Spain lynx births |date=2005 |accessdate= 5 September 2012 }}</ref> Over the following years, the number of births grew and additional breeding centers were opened. In March 2009, it was reported that 27 kittens had been born since the beginning of the program.<ref name=ap090320>{{cite news |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.com/huff-wires/20090320/eu-spain-lynx-cubs/ |title= Endangered Iberian lynx cubs born in Spain |agency= Associated Press |date= 20 March 2009 }}</ref> In 2009, the Spanish government planned to build a \u20ac5.5 million breeding center in [[Zarza de Granadilla]].<ref name=ap090320 /> In Portugal the Centro Nacional de Reprodu\u00e7\u00e3o do Lince-Ib\u00e9rico (CNRLI) established a breeding center in [[Silves, Portugal|Silves]].<ref name=TPN130627>{{cite news |url= http://theportugalnews.com/news/silves-born-iberian-lynx-released-in-spain/28733 |title= Silves-born Iberian lynx released in Spain |first= Carrie-Marie |last= Bratley |publisher= The Portugal News |date=2013 |access-date= 10 July 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140320154725/http://theportugalnews.com/news/silves-born-iberian-lynx-released-in-spain/28733 |archive-date= 20 March 2014 |url-status= dead}}</ref><ref name=expr130402>{{cite news |url= https://expresso.sapo.pt/quinze-crias-de-lince-iberico-nascem-em-silves=f797659 |title= Quinze crias de lince ib\u00e9rico nascem em Silves |language= Portuguese |trans-title=Fifteen Iberian lynx cubs born in Silves |work= Expresso.sapo.pt |first= Carla |last= Tom\u00e1s |first2= Andr\u00e9 |last2= de Atayde |date= 2 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThere were 14 surviving kittens in 2008 and 15 in 2009. In 2010, intense rain and health issues resulted in lower reproductive success\u201414 born, 8 surviving<ref name=rtve100818>{{cite news |url= http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20100818/fallece-geo-uno-cachorros-lince-iberico-nacido-cautividad-este-ano/347519.shtml |title= Fallece 'Geo', uno de los cachorros de lince ib\u00e9rico nacido en cautividad este a\u00f1o |language= Spanish |trans-title=Death of 'Geo', one of this season's captive-born Iberian lynx cubs |first= David |last= Sierra |publisher= rtve.es |date=2010}}</ref>\u2014but the next year, breeding centers recorded 45 births with 26 surviving kittens.<ref name=ep120617>{{cite news |url= http://www.europapress.es/sociedad/medio-ambiente-00647/noticia-nacen-59-ejemplares-lince-temporada-programa-cria-cautividad-20120617133403.html |title= Nacen 59 ejemplares de lince esta temporada en el Programa de Cr\u00eda en Cautividad |language= Spanish |trans-title=59 lynx kittens born this season as part of the Captive Breeding Program |work= Europa Press |date= 17 June 2012}}</ref> In 2012, breeding centers in Portugal and Spain reported a total of 44 survivors from 59 births,<ref name=ep120617 /> while 2013 saw a total of 44 survivors out of 53 born.<ref name=efe130909>{{cite news |url= http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/1914672/0/programa-cria/lince-iberico/acaba-con-44-cachorros/ |title= El programa de cr\u00eda en cautividad del lince ib\u00e9rico acaba la temporada con 44 cachorros |language= Spanish |trans-title=The lynx captive breeding program ends the season with 44 cubs |work= EFE |publisher= 20minutos.es |date=2013 }}</ref> In 2017, the total population of Iberian lynx reached 475 specimens.<ref>{{cite web|title=El lince ib\u00e9rico ampl\u00eda sus dominios y alcanza los 475 ejemplares, pese a la falta de conejos y los atropellos|url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/natural/20170202/413902666216/lince.html|publisher=La Vanguardia|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, it was reported that Iberian lynx embryos and oocytes had been collected and preserved for the first time. They were collected from Saliega and another female\u2014both sterilized and retired from the breeding program\u2014by Berlin's Leibniz Institute for Zoo and Wildlife Research and stored in liquid nitrogen at the [[Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales]] in Madrid for possible future breeding.<ref name=fvb130323>{{cite news |url= http://phys.org/news/2013-03-iberian-lynx-embryos.html |title= For the first time Iberian lynx embryos are collected and preserved |work= Forschungsverbund Berlin e.V. (FVB) |publisher= phys.org |date=2013}}</ref> In July 2014, the MNCN-CSIC announced they had produced sperm cells from the testicular tissue of sexually immature lynx.<ref name=mundo140722>{{cite news |url= http://www.elmundo.es/ciencia/2014/07/22/53ce2d5dca4741f5328b4574.html |title= Esperma 'de laboratorio' para salvar al lince ib\u00e9rico |language= Spanish |trans-title=Laboratory-made sperm to save the Iberian lynx |first= E. |last=Mosquera Rodriguez |work= [[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |date=2014 }}</ref>\n\nIberian lynx can be observed in captivity only at the Jerez Zoo,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.zoobotanicojerez.com/index.php?id=1476 |title= The Iberian Lynx at the Zoobotanico de Jerez (in Spanish)}}</ref> since December 2014 at the [[Lisbon Zoo]],<ref name=observador211214>{{cite news |url= http://observador.pt/especiais/os-felinos-mais-ameacados-mundo-ja-moram-em-lisboa/# |title= Os felinos mais ameacados do mundo ja moram em Lisboa |language= Portuguese |trans-title=O casal de linces-ib\u00e9ricos chegou ao Jardim Zool\u00f3gico de Lisboa com uma miss\u00e3o especial: mostrar aos visitantes o que os torna os felinos mais amea\u00e7ados do mundo |first= V. |last= Novais |work= Observador |date=2014}}</ref> and since July 2016 at the [[Madrid Zoo]].<ref name=zoomadrid200716>{{cite news |url= http://zoomadrid.com/sala-de-prensa/llega-a-zoo-aquarium-de-madrid-una-pareja-de-linces-ibericos-del-proyecto-iberlince |title=Llega a Zoo Aquarium de Madrid una pareja de linces ib\u00e9ricos del proyecto Iberlince |work= Zoo Aquarium Madrid |date= 20 July 2016 }}</ref>\nThe [[Jerez de la Frontera|Jerez]] animals integrate the breeding program, the two Lisbon lynxes were formerly in the Portuguese breeding center but are no longer suited for the program (the female had multiple failed pregnancies and the male has a form of epilepsy),<ref name=ultimoreduto17032015>{{cite news |url= http://oultimoreduto.blogspot.pt/2015/03/nova-visita-ao-zoo-de-lisboa-o-lince.html/# |title= Nova Visita ao Zoo de Lisboa \u2013 O Lince Ib\u00e9rico |language= Portuguese |trans-title= New visit to the Lisbon Zoo \u2013 The Iberian Lynx |first= Filipe |last= Figueiredo |work= O \u00daltimo Reduto |date=2015 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160210100603/http://oultimoreduto.blogspot.pt/2015/03/nova-visita-ao-zoo-de-lisboa-o-lince.html |archive-date= 10 February 2016 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> and the two Madrid lynxes were equally retired from the breeding program for not being suited for reproduction.\n\n== Genetic research==\nThe [[genetic diversity]] of the Iberian lynx is lower than in any other genetically impoverished felid, which is possibly a consequence of fragmentation and isolation of population units.{{r|Casas2013}} Iberian lynxes in Do\u00f1ana and Andujar differ genetically at [[microsatellite]] markers. Samples collected in Do\u00f1ana exhibited a high degree of [[inbreeding]] as this unit was isolated for a long time.<ref name=Casas2013>{{cite journal |journal=Molecular Ecology |title=Genetics at the verge of extinction: insights from the Iberian lynx |author1=Casas-Marce, M. |author2=Soriano, L. |author3=L\u00f3pez-Bao, J. V. |author4=Godoy, J. A. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2013 |doi=10.1111/mec.12498 |pmid= 24128177 |volume=22 |issue=22 |pages=5503\u20135515}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Cats|Mammals}}\n* [[Bobcat]], ''Lynx rufus''\n* [[Canadian lynx]], ''Lynx canadensis''\n* [[Eurasian lynx]], ''Lynx lynx''\n* ''[[Felicola isidoroi]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Lynx pardinus}}\n{{Wikispecies|Lynx pardinus}}\n* [http://www.lcie.org/ Large Carnivore Initiative for Europe \u2013 Iberian lynx]\n* [http://www.lynxexsitu.es/ Programa de Conservaci\u00f3n Ex-Situ] Official Spanish government page {{in lang|es}}\n* [http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=98 Species portrait Iberian lynx; IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group]\n* ARKive \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20060506121156/http://www.arkive.org/species/GES/mammals/Lynx_pardinus/ Images and movies of the Iberian lynx (''Lynx pardinus)'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130529082338/http://www.iberianature.com/material/iberianlynx.htm The natural history of the Iberian lynx]\n* [http://www.vertebradosibericos.org/mamiferos/lynpar.html Lynx in vertebradosibericos.org] {{in lang|es}}\n* [http://wwf.panda.org/about_our_earth/species/profiles/mammals/iberian_lynx/ WWF species profile: Iberian lynx]\n* [http://naturdata.com/Lynx-pardinus-25088.htm ''Lynx pardinus'' in Naturdata] {{in lang|pt}}\n\n{{Carnivora|Fe.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q129727}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Lynx]]\n[[Category:Endemic mammals of the Iberian Peninsula]]\n[[Category:EDGE species]]\n[[Category:Endangered animals]]\n[[Category:Endangered biota of Europe]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1827]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Small wild cat}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Iberian lynx\n| taxon = Lynx pardinus\n| authority = ([[Coenraad Jacob Temminck|Temminck]], 1827)\n| status = EN\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{Cite iucn |title=''Lynx pardinus'' |author=Rodr\u00edguez, A. |author2=Calzada, J. |last-author-amp=yes |page=e.T12520A50655794 |date=2015 |access-date=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n| image = Lince Ib\u00e9rico Do\u00f1ana.jpg\n| range_map = IberianLynx distribution2015.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Distribution of Iberian Lynx, 2015\n| fossil_range=[[Early Pleistocene]]<ref name=Boscaini_al2016>{{cite journal |author1=Boscaini, A. |last-author-amp=yes |author2=Alba, D.M. |author3=Beltr\u00e1n, J.F. |author4=Moya-Sola, S. |author5=Madurell-Malapeira, J. |year=2016 |title=Latest Early Pleistocene remains of ''Lynx pardinus'' (Carnivora, Felidae) from the Iberian Peninsula: taxonomy and evolutionary implications |journal=Quaternary Science Reviews |volume=143 |issue= |pages=96\u2013106 |doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2016.05.015 |url=}}</ref>-Recent {{Geological range|1.7|0}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Iberian lynx''' (''Lynx pardinus'') is a wild [[Felidae|cat]] [[Species (biological)|species]] [[endemic]] to the [[Iberian Peninsula]] in southwestern Europe. It is listed as [[endangered species|Endangered]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=iucn /> In the 20th century, the Iberian lynx population had declined because of overhunting and [[poaching]], fragmentation of suitable habitats; the population of its main prey species, the [[European rabbit]] (''Oryctolagus cuniculus''), experienced a severe decline caused by [[myxomatosis]] and [[rabbit haemorrhagic disease]].<ref name=Sim\u00f3n2012>{{cite book |author=Sim\u00f3n, M.A. |year=2012 |title=Ten years conserving the Iberian lynx |publisher=Consejer\u00eda de Agricultura, Pesca y Medio Ambiente. Junta de Andalus\u00eda |location=Seville |isbn=9788492807802|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VhFEETrncwEC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rodr\u00edguez-Hidalgo |first1=A. |last2=Lloveras |first2=L. |last3=Moreno-Garc\u00eda |first3=M. |last4=Saladi\u00e9 |first4=P. |last5=Canals |first5=A. |last6=Nadal |first6=J. |year=2013 |title=Feeding behaviour and taphonomic characterization of non-ingested rabbit remains produced by the Iberian lynx (''Lynx pardinus'') |journal=Journal of Archaeological Science |volume=40 |issue=7 |pages=3031\u20133045 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/236208653 |doi=10.1016/j.jas.2013.03.006 |hdl=10261/153608}}</ref><ref name=Fordham2013>{{cite journal |last1=Fordham |first1=D.A. |last2=Ak\u00e7akaya |first2=H.R. |last3=Brook |first3=B.W. |last4=Rodr\u00edguez |first4=A. |last5=Alves |first5=P.C. |last6=Civantos |first6=E. |last7=Trivino |first7=M. |last8=Watts |first8=M.J. |last9=Araujo |first9=M.B. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2013 |title=Adapted conservation measures are required to save the Iberian lynx in a changing climate |journal=Nature Climate Change |volume=3 |issue=10 |pages=899\u2013903 |bibcode=2013NatCC...3..899F |hdl=10261/84387 |doi=10.1038/nclimate1954 |url=http://digital.csic.es/bitstream/10261/84387/1/Fordham_Nat%20Clim%20Change_13.pdf}}</ref>\n\nBy the turn of the 21st century, the Iberian lynx was on the verge of extinction, as only about 100 individuals survived in two isolated subpopulations in [[Andalusia]]. Conservation measures were implemented since 2002 which included improving habitat, restocking of rabbits, [[Translocation (wildlife conservation)|translocating]],  [[Species reintroduction|re-introducing]] and monitoring Iberian lynxes. By 2012, the population had increased to 326 individuals.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lopez |first1=G. |last2=Lopez |first2=M. |last3=Fernandez |first3=L. |last4=Ruiz |first4=G. |last5=Arenas|first5=R. |last6=Del Rey |first6=T. |last7=Gil |first7=J.M. |last8=Garrote |first8=G. |last9=Garcia |first9=M. |last10=Simon |first10=M. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2012 |title=Population development of the Iberian lynx since 2002 |journal=Cat News |volume=57 |page=34}}</ref>\n\nIt is a [[monotypic]] species and is thought to have evolved from ''[[Lynx issiodorensis]]''.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n''Felis pardina'' was the [[scientific name]] proposed by [[Coenraad Jacob Temminck]] in 1827 who described skins of Iberian lynxes that were killed in the area of the [[Tagus]] river in Portugal and were traded in Paris and London.<ref>{{cite book |last=Temminck, C. J. |year=1827 |title=Monographies de mammalogie, ou description de quelques genres de mammif\u00e8res, dont les esp\u00e8ces ont \u00e9t\u00e9 observ\u00e9es dans les diff\u00e9rens mus\u00e9es de l'Europe. Vol. 1 |location=Leiden |publisher=C. C. Vander Hoek |chapter=''Felis pardina'' |pages=116\u2212117 |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/monographiedema00temm/page/116}}</ref>\nIt is a [[monotypic]] species.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten, C. |author3=Eizirik, E. |author4=Gentry, A. |author5=Werdelin, L. |author6=Wilting, A. |author7=Yamaguchi, N. |author8=Abramov, A. V. |author9=Christiansen, P. |author10=Driscoll, C. |author11=Duckworth, J. W. |author12=Johnson, W. |author13=Luo, S.-J. |author14=Meijaard, E. |author15=O\u2019Donoghue, P. |author16=Sanderson, J. |author17=Seymour, K. |author18=Bruford, M. |author19=Groves, C. |author20=Hoffmann, M. |author21=Nowell, K. |author22=Timmons, Z. |author23=Tobe, S. |year=2017 |title=A revised taxonomy of the Felidae: The final report of the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group |journal=Cat News |volume=Special Issue 11 |pages=45 |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/32616/A_revised_Felidae_Taxonomy_CatNews.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y#page=45}}</ref>\n\n=== Evolution ===\nThe Iberian lynx is thought to have evolved from ''[[Lynx issiodorensis]]''.<ref name=pmoe68>{{cite book |first= B. |last= Kurt\u00e9n |title=Pleistocene Mammals of Europe |year=1968 |publisher=Aldine Transaction |location=London, New Brunswick}}</ref>\nThe earliest [[fossil]] remains of the Iberian lynx date to the [[Early Pleistocene]].<ref name=Boscaini_al2016/>\n\n== Characteristics ==\nThe Iberian lynx has a short bright yellowish to tawny coloured spotted fur. The spots vary in shape and size from small round to elongate. They are arranged in lines and decrease in size from the back towards the sides.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Beltr\u00e1n |first1=J.F. |last2=Delibes |first2=M. |year=1993 |title=Physical characteristics of Iberian lynxes (''Lynx pardinus'') from Do\u00f1ana, southwestern Spain |journal=Journal of Mammalogy |volume=74 |issue=4 |pages=852\u2013862 |doi=10.2307/1382423 |jstor=1382423}}</ref>\nIts head is small with tufted ears and a ruff. Its body is short with long legs and a short tail. Head and body length of males is {{convert|74.7-82|cm|abbr=on}} with a {{convert|12.5-16|cm|abbr=on}} long tail and a weight of {{convert|7-15.9|kg|abbr=on}}. Females are smaller with a head-to-body-length of approximately {{convert|68.2-77.5|cm|abbr=on}} and a weight of {{convert|9.2-10|kg|abbr=on}}.<ref name=WCoW>{{cite book |first=M. |last=Sunquist |first2=F. |last2=Sunquist |last-author-amp=yes |year=2002 |title=Wild cats of the World |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago |isbn=978-0-226-77999-7 |chapter=Iberian Lynx ''Lynx pardinus'' (Temminck, 1827) |pages=177\u2013184 |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/wildcatsofworld00sunq/page/177}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\nThe Iberian lynx was once present throughout the Iberian Peninsula and southern France. In the 1950s, the northern population extended from the [[Mediterranean]] to [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] and parts of northern Portugal, and the southern population from central to southern Spain.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Clavero |first1=M. |last2=Delibes |first2=M. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2013 |title=Using historical accounts to set conservation baselines: the case of Lynx species in Spain |journal=Biodiversity and Conservation |volume=22 |issue=8 |pages=1691\u20131702 |doi=10.1007/s10531-013-0506-4 |hdl=10261/80444|hdl-access=free }}</ref> Populations declined from 15 subpopulations in the 1940s to only two subpopulations in the early 1990s, most noticeably in [[Montes de Toledo]] and [[Sierra Morena]]. Before 1973, it was present in [[Sierra de Gata]], Montes de Toledo, eastern Sierra Morena, Sierra de Relumbrar and coastal plains in the Do\u00f1ana area. Between the early 1960s and 2000, it has lost about 80% of its former range.<ref name=AC2008>{{cite journal |last1=Alda |first1=F. |last2=Inog\u00e9s |first2=J. |last3=Alcaraz |first3=L. |last4=Oria |first4=J. |last5=Aranda |first5=A. |last6=Doadrio |first6=I. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2008 |title=Looking for the Iberian lynx in central Spain: a needle in a hay stack? |journal=Animal Conservation |volume=11 |issue=4 |pages=297\u2013305 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2008.00185.x}}</ref><ref name=JM2011>{{cite journal |last1=Gil-Sanchez |first1=J.M. |last2=McCain |first2=E.B. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2011 |title=Former range and decline of the Iberian lynx (''Lynx pardinus'') reconstructed using verified records |journal=Journal of Mammalogy |volume=92 |issue=5 |pages=1081\u20131090 |doi=10.1644/10-MAMM-A-381.1|doi-access=free }}</ref> It is now restricted to very limited areas in southern Spain, with breeding only confirmed in Sierra Morena and Do\u00f1ana coastal plains.<ref name=Sim\u00f3n2012/>\n\n[[Fossil]] remains indicate that the Iberian lynx had a wider range during the [[Late Pleistocene]] and [[Holocene]]. Five lynx remains found in [[Arene Candide]] in northern Italy date to about 24,820\u201318,620 [[before present]]. One specimen found in Cabias cave in southern France was [[radiocarbon date]]d to 3780\u00b190 before present.<ref name=QSR150315>{{cite journal |title=Ancient DNA evidence of Iberian lynx palaeoendemism |journal=Quaternary Science Reviews |volume=112 |pages=172\u2013180 |date=2015 |doi=10.1016/j.quascirev.2015.01.009 |last1=Rodr\u00edguez-Varela |first1=R. |last2=Tagliacozzo |first2=A. |last3=Ure\u00f1a |first3=I. |last4=Garc\u00eda |first4=N. |last5=Cr\u00e9gut-Bonnoure |first5=E. |last6=Mannino |first6=M. A. |last7=Arsuaga |first7=J. L. |last8=Valdiosera |first8=C. |last-author-amp=yes |bibcode=2015QSRv..112..172R |url= }}</ref>\n\nThe Iberian lynx prefers [[heterogeneous]] environments of open grassland mixed with dense shrubs such as [[Arbutus unedo|strawberry tree]], [[Pistacia lentiscus|mastic]], and [[juniper]], and trees such as [[holm oak]] and [[cork oak]]. It is now largely restricted to mountainous areas.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\nThe Iberian lynx [[Spraying (animal behavior)|marks its territory with its urine]], scratch marks on the barks of trees, and scat. The home ranges of adults are stable over many years.<ref name=WCoW />\nCamera trapping surveys in the eastern Sierra Morena Mountains between 1999 and 2008 revealed that six females had home ranges of {{convert|5.2-6.6|km2|abbr=on}}. Four males in the area had home ranges of {{convert|11.8-12.2|km2|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Gil-S\u00e1nchez, J.M. |last-author-amp=yes |author2=Moral, M. |author3=Bueno, J. |author4=Rodr\u00edguez-Siles, J. |author5=Lillo, S. |author6=P\u00e9rez, J. |author7=Mart\u00edn, J.M. |author8=Valenzuela, G. |author9=Garrote, G. |author10=Torralba, B. |author11=Sim\u00f3n-Mata, M.\u00c1. |year=2011 |title=The use of camera trapping for estimating Iberian lynx (''Lynx pardinus'') home ranges |journal=European Journal of Wildlife Research |volume=57 |issue=6 |pages=1203\u20131211 |doi=10.1007/s10344-011-0533-y |citeseerx=10.1.1.459.5581 }}</ref>\n\n=== Diet and hunting ===\n{{Multiple image |direction=vertical |align=top |header=Iberian lynx hunting [[common quail]] (''Coturnix coturnix'')\n|image1=Iberian Lynx catching his prey.jpg |caption1=Swiping with right paw with claws extended\n|image2=Iberian Lynx eating bird.jpg |caption2=Caught prey in mouth}}\nThe Iberian lynx preys foremost on the [[European rabbit]] (''Oryctolagus cuniculus'') for the bulk of its diet, supplemented by [[red-legged partridge]] (''Alectoris rufa''), [[rodent]]s and to a smaller degree also on wild [[ungulate]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Palomares  |first1=F. |last2=Delibes |first2=M. |last3=Revilla |first3=E. |last4=Calzada |first4=J. |last5=Frediani |first5=J.M. |year=2001 |title=Spatial ecology of Iberian lynx and abundance of European rabbits in south-western Spain |jstor=3830752 |journal=Wildlife Monographs |volume=148 |issue=148 |pages=1\u201336}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gil-S\u00e1nchez |first1=J.M. |last2=Ballesteros-Duper\u00f3n |first2=E. |last3=Bueno-Segura |first3=J.F. |year=2006 |title=Feeding ecology of the Iberian lynx ''Lynx pardinus'' in eastern Sierra Morena (Southern Spain) |journal=Acta Theriologica |volume= 51 |pages= 85\u201390 |doi=10.1007/bf03192659}}</ref><ref name=LopezBao2011>{{cite journal |last1=L\u00f3pez\u2010Bao |first1=J.V. |last2=Palomares |first2=F. |last3=Rodr\u00edguez |first3=A. |last4=Ferreras |first4=P. |title=Intraspecific interference influences the use of prey hotspots |journal=Oikos |volume=120 |issue=10 |year=2011 |pages=1489\u20131496 |doi= 10.1111/j.1600-0706.2011.19194.x |hdl=10261/39785|hdl-access=free }}</ref>\nIt sometimes preys on young [[fallow deer]] (''Dama dama''), [[roe deer]] (''Capreolus capreolus''), [[mouflon]] (''Ovis orientalis''), and ducks.<ref name=DelibesRod2000>{{cite book |last=Delibes |first=A. |last2=Rodr\u00edguez |first2=M. |last3=Ferreras |first3=P. |title=Action Plan for the Conservation of the Iberian Lynx in Europe (''Lynx pardinus'') |date=2000 |publisher=Council of Europe |isbn=978-92-871-4423-2 |url=http://digital.csic.es/bitstream/10261/59779/1/SN111-E.pdf}}</ref> A male requires one rabbit per day while a female raising kittens will eat three per day.<ref name=ward>{{cite book |url=http://wardenvironment.ch/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Ward_REP_The_Iberian_lynx_emergency.pdf |first=D. |last=Ward |title=The Iberian Lynx Emergency |year=2004 |publisher=EU commissioned report}}</ref>\n\nThe Iberian species has low adaptability\u2014it continued to rely heavily on rabbits (75% of its food intake) despite the latter's repeated population crashes due to [[myxomatosis]] and [[rabbit haemorrhagic disease]].<ref name=Fordham2013/>\n\nIt competes for prey with [[red fox]] (''Vulpes vulpes''), [[Egyptian mongoose]] (''Herpestes ichneumon'') and [[European wildcat]] (''Felis silvestris''). Also, it often kills other smaller carnivores such as red fox, Egyptian mongoose and [[common genet]] (''Genetta genetta'').<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fedriani |first1=J. M. |last2=Palomares |first2=F. |last3=Delibes |first3=M. |year=1999 |title=Niche relations among three sympatric Mediterranean carnivores |url= |journal=Oecologia |volume=121 |issue=1 |pages=138\u2013148 |doi=10.1007/s004420050915 |pmid=28307883 |bibcode=1999Oecol.121..138F |citeseerx=10.1.1.587.7215}}</ref> The species is solitary and hunts alone; it will stalk its prey or lie in wait for hours behind a bush or rock until the prey is sufficiently close to pounce in a few strides.\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n[[File:Iberian_Lynx_cub_07.jpg|thumb|Iberian lynx cub]]\nDuring the mating season the female leaves her territory in search of a male. The typical [[gestation]] period is about two months; the kittens are born between March and September, with a peak of births in March and April. A litter consists of two or three (rarely one, four or five) kittens weighing between {{convert|200|and|250|g|oz}}.\n\nThe kittens become independent at 7 to 10 months old, but remain with the mother until around 20 months old. Survival of the young depends heavily on the availability of prey species. In the wild, both males and females reach sexual maturity at the age of one year, though in practice they rarely breed until a territory becomes vacant; one female was known not to breed until five years old when its mother died. The maximum longevity in the wild is 13 years.<ref name=iucncsg>{{cite web |url= http://lynx.uio.no/jon/lynx/lynxib01.htm |title= Iberian lynx ''Lynx pardinus'' |publisher= IUCN Cat Specialist Group |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110724185701/http://lynx.uio.no/jon/lynx/lynxib01.htm |archive-date= 24 July 2011 |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=adw>{{cite web |url= http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Lynx_pardinus.html |title= ''Lynx pardinus'' |publisher= Animal Diversity Web }}</ref>\n\nSiblings become violent towards one another between 30 and 60 days, peaking at 45 days. A kitten will frequently kill its littermate in a brutal fight. It is unknown why these episodes of aggression occur, though many scientists believe it is related to a change in hormones when a kitten switches from its mother's milk to meat. Others believe it is related to hierarchy, and \"[[survival of the fittest]]\".\n\nDifficulty in finding mates has led to more inbreeding, which results in fewer kittens and a greater rate of non-traumatic death.<ref name=EJWR2012>{{cite journal |first=F. |last=Palomares |first2=J. A. |last2=Godoy |first3=J. V. |last3=Lopez-Bao |title=Possible Extinction Vortex for a Population of Iberian Lynx on the Verge of Extirpation |journal=Conservation Biology |volume=26 |issue=4 |pages=689\u2013697 |year=2012 |doi=10.1111/j.1523-1739.2012.01870.x |pmid= 22731698 |hdl=10261/55052|hdl-access=free }}</ref> Inbreeding leads to lower semen quality and greater rates of infertility in males, hindering efforts to increase the species' fitness.<ref name=CB2013>{{cite journal |first=M. J. |last=Ruiz-Lopez |first2=N. |last2=Ganan |first3=J. A. |last3=Godoy |title=Heterozygosity-Fitness Correlations and Inbreeding Depression in two Critically Endangered Mammals |journal=Conservation Biology |volume=26 |issue=1 |pages=1121\u20131129 |year=2013 |doi=10.1111/j.1523-1739.2012.01916.x |pmid=22897325 |hdl=10261/63937}}</ref>\n\n== Threats ==\nThe Iberian lynx is threatened by habitat loss, road accidents and illegal hunting.<ref name=iucn/> Habitat loss is due mainly to infrastructure improvement, urban and resort development and tree mono cultivation, which fragments the lynx's distribution. In the 20th century, rabbit diseases such as [[myxomatosis]] and [[Rabbit haemorrhagic disease|hemorrhagic disease]] resulted in a dramatic decline of its main prey.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Ecosystem Effects of Variant Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease Virus, Iberian Peninsula |first1=M. |last1=Delibes-Mateos |first2=C. |last2=Ferreira |first3=F. |last3=Carro |first4=M. A. |last4=Escudero |first5=C. |last5=Gort\u00e1zar |last-author-amp=yes |journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases |volume=20 |issue=12 |pages=2166\u20132168 |year=2014 |doi=10.3201/eid2012.140517 |pmid=25417710 |pmc=4257825}}</ref> Illegal traps set for rabbits and foxes were leading causes for lynx fatality in the 1990s.<ref name=BC1992>{{cite journal |last1=Ferreras |first1=P. |last2=Aldama |first2=J.J. |last3=Beltran |first3=J. |last4=Delibes |first4=M. |last-author-amp=yes |year=1992 |title=Rates and causes of mortality in a fragmented population of Iberian lynx ''Felis pardina'' Temminck, 1824 |url= |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=62 |issue=3 |pages=197\u2013202 |doi=10.1016/0006-3207(92)91116-a |hdl=10261/50936|hdl-access=free }}</ref>\nEvery year, several Iberian lynxes die when trying to cross highways with heavy traffic.<ref name=Sim\u00f3n2012/> In 2013, 14 Iberian lynxes died on roads, and 21 in 2014.<ref name=EFE140101>{{cite news |url=http://www.andalucesdiario.es/provincias/huelva/el-atropello-mortal-de-14-linces-en-2013-merma-la-recuperacion-de-la-especie/ |title=El atropello mortal de 14 linces en 2013 merma la recuperaci\u00f3n de la especie |language=Spanish |trans-title=14 lynxes were fatally run over in 2013, undermining the species' recovery |newspaper=Andaluces Diario |date=2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106081726/http://www.andalucesdiario.es/provincias/huelva/el-atropello-mortal-de-14-linces-en-2013-merma-la-recuperacion-de-la-especie/ |archive-date=6 January 2014 |url-status=dead |access-date=6 January 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Pais150219>{{cite news |url= http://elpais.com/elpais/2015/02/16/inenglish/1424097857_034701.html |title=Rise in Iberian lynx road deaths speeds up protection plans |first=G. |last=Donaire |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |date=2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, several individuals died of [[feline leukemia]].<ref>{{cite journal |author1=L\u00f3pez, G. |last-author-amp=yes |author2=L\u00f3pez-Parra, M. |author3=Fern\u00e1ndez, L. |author4=Mart\u00ednez-Granados, C. |author5=Mart\u00ednez, F. |author6=Meli, M.L. |author7=Gil-S\u00e1nchez, J.M. |author8=Viqueira, N. |author9=D\u00edaz-Portero, M.A. |author10=Cadenas, R. |author11=Lutz, H. |author12=Vargas, A. |author13=Sim\u00f3n, M.A. |year=2009 |title=Management measures to control a feline leukemia virus outbreak in the endangered Iberian lynx |journal=Animal Conservation |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=173\u2013182 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2009.00241.x }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Palomares, F. |last-author-amp=yes |author2=L\u00f3pez-Bao, J.V. |author3=Rodr\u00edguez, A. |year=2011 |title=Feline leukaemia virus outbreak in the endangered Iberian lynx and the role of feeding stations: a cautionary tale |journal=Animal Conservation |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=242\u2013245 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2010.00403.x|hdl=10261/39812 |hdl-access=free }}</ref>  \n\nIn 2013, it was reported that the Iberian lynx possesses antibiotic resistant bacteria within its digestive tract, which may lead to more dangerous and difficult-to-treat infections and decrease the cat's fitness.<ref>{{cite journal |first=A. |last=Gon\u00e7alves |first2=G. |last2=Igrejas |first3=T. |last3=Hajer |last-author-amp=yes |title=Detection of antibiotic resistant enterococci and ''Escherichia coli'' in free range Iberian Lynx (''Lynx pardinus'') |journal=Science of the Total Environment |volume=456\u2013457 |pages=115\u2013119 |year=2013 |doi=10.1016/j.scitotenv.2013.03.073 |pmid=23588135 |bibcode=2013ScTEn.456..115G}}</ref> A 2013 study suggests climate change may threaten the Iberian lynx species due to their inability to adapt well to a climate change or it may lead them to relocate to areas that have a more suitable climate but fewer rabbits, increasing mortality.<ref name=Fordham2013/>\n\n== Conservation ==\n[[File:Linces10.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Iberian lynx]]\nThe Iberian lynx is fully protected. It is listed on [[CITES Appendix I]], on Appendix II of the [[Berne Convention on the Conservation of European Wildlife and Natural Habitats]] and on Annexes II and IV of the [[Habitats Directive]] of the [[European Union]]. It has been listed as Endangered on the IUCN Red List since 2014.<ref name=iucn />\n\nConservation measures include restoring its native habitat, maintaining the wild rabbit population, reducing unnatural causes of death, and releasing captive bred individuals.<ref name=Vargas2008>{{cite journal |authors=Vargas, A., S\u00e1nchez, I., Mart\u00ednez, F., Rivas, A., Godoy, J.A., Roldan, E., Sim\u00f3n, M.A., Serra, R., Perez, M.A.J., Ensenat, C. and Delibes, M. |year=2008 |title=The Iberian lynx ''Lynx pardinus'' Conservation Breeding Program |journal=International Zoo Yearbook |volume=42 |pages=190\u2013198 |doi=10.1111/j.1748-1090.2007.00036.x |hdl=10261/50244 |url=http://digital.csic.es/bitstream/10261/50244/3/105225.pdf}}</ref> \nThe Spanish National Commission for the Protection of Nature endorsed the Iberian Lynx Ex Situ Conservation Breeding Program to serve as a \"safety net\" by managing the captive population and also to \"help establish new Iberian lynx free-ranging populations through reintroduction programmes.\" Before release of captive-bred cats, their natural habit may be simulated to prepare them for life in the wild.<ref name=Vargas2008 /> A 2006 study used a non-intrusive monitoring system involving cameras to monitor the demographics of both lynxes and rabbits residing in Sierra Morena. Supplemental food sources could be provided if wild rabbits suffered a decline.<ref name=GilSanchez2010>{{cite journal |first=J. |last=Gil-S\u00e1nchez |first2=M. |last2=Sim\u00f3n |first3=R. |last3=Cadenas |first4=J. |last4=Bueno |first5=M. |last5=Moral |first6=J. |last6=Rodr\u00edguez-Siles |year=2010 |title=Current Status Of the Iberian Lynx (''Lynx pardinus'') in eastern Sierra Morena, Southern Spain |journal=Wildlife Biology in Practice |volume=6 |issue=3 |pages=14\u201333 |doi=10.2461/wbp.lynx.2 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/228505844}}</ref>\n\nManagement efforts are being developed to conserve and restore the animal's native range.<ref name=Clavero2013>{{cite journal |last1=Clavero |first1=M. |last2=Delibes |first2=M. |year=2013 |title=Using historical accounts to set conservation baselines: the case of Lynx species in Spain |journal=Biodiversity Conservation Journal |volume=22 |issue=8 |pages=1691\u20131702 |doi=10.1007/s10531-013-0506-4|hdl=10261/80444|hdl-access=free }}</ref> Officials intending to release captive-bred lynx look for areas of appropriate habitat, rabbit abundance, and acceptance by the local human population.<ref name=NL130621>{{cite news |url= https://naturlink.sapo.pt/Noticias/Noticias/content/Lince-iberico-Jazz-e-Joaninha-que-nasceram-em-Silves-em-2012-foram-hoje-libertados-na-Andaluzia?bl=1 |title=Lince-ib\u00e9rico: Jazz e Joaninha, que nasceram em Silves em 2012, foram hoje libertados na Andaluzia |language= Portuguese |trans-title= Iberian lynx: Jazz and Joaninha, who were born in Silves in 2012, were released today in Andalusia |first= F. |last= Alves |work= Naturlink |date= 21 June 2013 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130630230952/http://naturlink.sapo.pt/Noticias/Noticias/content/Lince-iberico-Jazz-e-Joaninha-que-nasceram-em-Silves-em-2012-foram-hoje-libertados-na-Andaluzia?bl=1 |archive-date= 30 June 2013 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> About 90 million euros was spent on various conservation measures between 1994 and 2013.<ref name=UA130722>{{cite news |url= http://www.adelaide.edu.au/news/news63241.html |title= Iberian lynx threatened by climate change |publisher= The University of Adelaide |date= 22 July 2013 }}</ref> The [[European Union]] contributes up to 61% of funding.<ref name=elpais131215>{{cite news |url= http://elpais.com/elpais/2013/12/15/inenglish/1387110752_809462.html |title= Iberian lynx faces new threat as disease decimates rabbit population |first= J. |last= Vi\u00fadez |work= El Pais |date= 15 December 2013 }}</ref><ref name=efe091003>{{cite news |url= http://www.abc.es/hemeroteca/historico-03-10-2009/abc/Sociedad/el-lince-iberico-inicia-una-incierta-reconquista_103358912739.html |title= El lince ib\u00e9rico inicia una incierta <<reconquista>> |language= Spanish |trans-title=The Iberian lynx begins an uncertain \"reconquest\" |work= EFE |publisher= ABC.es |date=2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Reintroduction programme ===\n[[File:Poblaci\u00f3n lince.jpg|thumb|Graph showing Iberian lynx population in Spain, 1960\u20132007]]\nBeginning in 2009, the Iberian lynx was reintroduced into [[Embalse de Guadalmellato|Guadalmellato]], resulting in a population of 23 in 2013.<ref name=eleco130408>{{cite news |url= http://ecodiario.eleconomista.es/espana/noticias/4730656/04/13/la-junta-de-andalucia-refuerza-en-el-guadalmellato-la-poblacion-de-lince-iberico-con-la-suelta-de-dos-ejemplares.html |title= La Junta de Andaluc\u00eda refuerza en el Guadalmellato la poblaci\u00f3n de lince ib\u00e9rico con la suelta de dos ejemplares |language= Spanish |trans-title=Andalusia reinforces Iberian lynx population in Guadalmellato with the release of two individuals |work= El Economista |date= 8 April 2013 }}</ref> Since 2010, the species has also been released in Guarrizas.<ref name=NL130621 /><ref name=decpaper>{{cite web |url= http://www.iberianature.com/material/documents/LynxBrief12E.pdf |title= LynxBrief |last=Ward |first= D. |date=2008}}</ref> Discussions were held with the Ministry of Environment on plans for releases in the Campanarios de Azaba area near [[Salamanca]].<ref name=rewild>{{cite web |url=http://rewildingeurope.com/news/articles/wildlife-returns-to-western-iberia/ |title=Wildlife returns to Western Iberia |publisher=Rewilding Europe |date=2012}}</ref> In April 2013, it was reported that Andalusia's total wild population\u2014only 94 in 2002\u2014had tripled to 309 individuals.<ref name=elmundo130409>{{cite news |url= http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2013/04/08/andalucia/1365443569.html |title=La poblaci\u00f3n de linces se triplica en Andaluc\u00eda en los \u00faltimos diez a\u00f1os |language= Spanish |trans-title=The lynx population has tripled in Andalusia in the last ten years |newspaper=El Mundo |date=2013}}</ref><ref name=eleco130408 /> In July 2013, environmental groups confirmed the presence of a wild-born litter in the [[Province of C\u00e1ceres]] ([[Extremadura]]).<ref name=efe130706>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.es/agencias/noticia.asp?noticia=1453396 |title= Grupos ecologistas confirman que el lince ib\u00e9rico cr\u00eda en libertad en C\u00e1ceres |language= Spanish |trans-title=Environmental group confirm the Iberian lynx is breeding in the wild in C\u00e1ceres |work= [[EFE]] |publisher= ABC.es |date=2013}}</ref> A study published in July 2013 in ''Nature Climate Change'' advised that reintroduction programs take place in northern Iberia, suggesting that climate change would threaten rabbits in the south.<ref name=UA130722 /><ref name=LS130721>{{cite news |url= http://www.livescience.com/38330-climate-change-iberian-lynx-extinction.html |title= Climate Change Could Wipe Out Iberian Lynx |first= Tia |last= Ghose |publisher= Live Science |date=2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 November 2014, 8 Iberian lynxes were released into [[Toledo, Spain]]; one of them traveled near [[Madrid]], the first time in 40 years.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://elpais.com/elpais/2015/03/09/inenglish/1425900807_150674.html|title= Iberian Lynx returns to Madrid region after 40 years|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 10 March 2015|website= |publisher= El Pais}}</ref>\n\nThe presence of Iberian lynxes in Portugal, particularly in the south, has been verified.<ref name=pu130601>{{cite news |url= http://www.publico.pt/n1596143 |title= Lince ib\u00e9rico, o mais amea\u00e7ado dos felinos, fotografado em Milfontes |language= Portuguese |trans-title=The Iberian Lynx, the most threatened feline, was photographed in Milfontes |first= M. |last=Soares |work=Publico.pt |date=2013}}</ref> In 2014, the [[Institute for Nature Conservation and Forests]] signed contracts securing 2,000 hectares of land for Portugal's reintroduction project.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lynx pardinas (2000)|url=http://www.icnf.pt/portal/naturaclas/rn2000/resource/docs/rn-plan-set/mamif/lynx-pardinus/|website=ICNF Portal|publisher=ICN:B|accessdate=27 June 2017|language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>[http://www.icnf.pt/portal/naturaclas/rn2000/resource/docs/rn-plan-set/mamif/lynx-pardinus/ ''Lynx pardinus'']. Instituto da Conserva\u00e7\u00e3o da Natureza e das Florestas, Portugal</ref><ref name=PN141113>{{cite news |url= http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/more-space-in-portugal-in-pipeline-for-iberian-lynx/33215 |title= More space in Portugal in pipeline for Iberian Lynx |first= Carrie-Marie |last= Bratley |work= The Portugal News |date= 13 November 2014 |access-date= 8 December 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141208113934/http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/more-space-in-portugal-in-pipeline-for-iberian-lynx/33215 |archive-date= 8 December 2014 |url-status= dead }}</ref> On 16 December 2014, a pair of Iberian lynx was released into [[Guadiana Valley Natural Park]] near [[M\u00e9rtola]], Portugal.<ref name=PN141218>{{cite news |url= http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/portugal-makes-history-with-first-release-of-iberian-lynx/33484 |title=Portugal makes history with first release of Iberian Lynx |work= The Portugal News |date= 18 December 2014}}</ref>\nOn 7 February 2015, another pair was released into the park, but the female was later found dead on 12 March 2015 after being poisoned in M\u00e9rtola.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/iberian-lynx-female-released-last-month-found-dead/34313|title= Iberian Lynx female released last month found dead|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 19 March 2015|website= |publisher= The Portugal News}}</ref> The last pair of captive-bred Iberian lynxes were released into Guadiana Valley Nature Reserve on 12 May 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/final-two-iberian-lynx-released-into-the-wild/34765|title= Final two Iberian Lynx released into the wild|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 14 May 2015|website= theportugalnews.com|publisher= The Portugal News}}</ref> By the end of 2015 there were 400 lynx on the Iberian peninsula, the vast majority in Andalusia, in southern Spain, but with smaller new populations in the hills near Toledo, in Extremadura (south-western Spain) and in southern Portugal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-35890789|title=The return of the lynx|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=28 March 2016|website=bbc.com|publisher=BBC|access-date=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe reintroduction of Iberian lynx in Portugal has been a success; from 17 animals that were reintroduced, 12 have already established territories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wilder.pt/historias/comecou-hoje-a-epoca-de-2017-de-libertacoes-de-linces-em-portugal/|title=Come\u00e7ou a \u00e9poca de 2017 de liberta\u00e7\u00f5es de linces em Portugal|date=17 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nSince a 2007 outbreak of [[feline leukemia virus]] (FeLV), wild lynxes are tested periodically for possible disease. September\u2013December 2013 samples were negative for FeLV but one male became the first of his species to test positive for [[feline immunodeficiency virus]] (FIV) and was placed into quarantine.<ref name=EP131230>{{cite news |url= http://noticias.lainformacion.com/salud/vacunas/resultado-negativo-en-los-chequeos-a-linces-para-detectar-leucemia-felina-con-un-positivo-de-virus-de-inmunodeficiencia_R1VgBI0UVEw0VXpuAsbjm7/ |title= Resultado negativo en los chequeos a linces para detectar leucemia felina, con un positivo de virus de inmunodeficiencia |language= Spanish |trans-title=Lynxes negative for feline leukemia but one positive for immunodeficiency virus |work= Europa Press |publisher= La Informacion |date=2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131231083837/http://noticias.lainformacion.com/salud/vacunas/resultado-negativo-en-los-chequeos-a-linces-para-detectar-leucemia-felina-con-un-positivo-de-virus-de-inmunodeficiencia_R1VgBI0UVEw0VXpuAsbjm7/ |archive-date= 31 December 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n=== Captive breeding ===\n[[File:Iberian Lynx CNRLI reproduction centre 10 May 2015 (15).JPG|thumb|The Iberian Lynx CNRLI reproduction centre near the village of Vale Fuzeiros near the town of [[Silves, Portugal]]]]\nIn 2002, the Jerez Zoo confirmed it had three females and was developing a plan for a captive breeding program. One of those females was [[Saliega]], captured as a kitten in April 2002.<ref name=guard0204>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/apr/21/highereducation.biologicalscience |title= Captured cubs hold future of Europe's tiger |publisher= The Guardian |date= April 2002 |location=London |first=E. |last=Gon\u00e7alves}}</ref> She became the first Iberian lynx to breed in captivity, giving birth to three healthy kittens on 29 March 2005 at the El Acebuche Breeding Center, in the Do\u00f1ana Nature Park in [[Huelva]], Spain.<ref name=bbc050330>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/4394005.stm |work=BBC News |title=Hopes raised by Spain lynx births |date=2005 |accessdate= 5 September 2012 }}</ref> Over the following years, the number of births grew and additional breeding centers were opened. In March 2009, it was reported that 27 kittens had been born since the beginning of the program.<ref name=ap090320>{{cite news |url= http://www.huffingtonpost.com/huff-wires/20090320/eu-spain-lynx-cubs/ |title= Endangered Iberian lynx cubs born in Spain |agency= Associated Press |date= 20 March 2009 }}</ref> In 2009, the Spanish government planned to build a \u20ac5.5 million breeding center in [[Zarza de Granadilla]].<ref name=ap090320 /> In Portugal the Centro Nacional de Reprodu\u00e7\u00e3o do Lince-Ib\u00e9rico (CNRLI) established a breeding center in [[Silves, Portugal|Silves]].<ref name=TPN130627>{{cite news |url= http://theportugalnews.com/news/silves-born-iberian-lynx-released-in-spain/28733 |title= Silves-born Iberian lynx released in Spain |first= Carrie-Marie |last= Bratley |publisher= The Portugal News |date=2013 |access-date= 10 July 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140320154725/http://theportugalnews.com/news/silves-born-iberian-lynx-released-in-spain/28733 |archive-date= 20 March 2014 |url-status= dead}}</ref><ref name=expr130402>{{cite news |url= https://expresso.sapo.pt/quinze-crias-de-lince-iberico-nascem-em-silves=f797659 |title= Quinze crias de lince ib\u00e9rico nascem em Silves |language= Portuguese |trans-title=Fifteen Iberian lynx cubs born in Silves |work= Expresso.sapo.pt |first= Carla |last= Tom\u00e1s |first2= Andr\u00e9 |last2= de Atayde |date= 2 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThere were 14 surviving kittens in 2008 and 15 in 2009. In 2010, intense rain and health issues resulted in lower reproductive success\u201414 born, 8 surviving<ref name=rtve100818>{{cite news |url= http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20100818/fallece-geo-uno-cachorros-lince-iberico-nacido-cautividad-este-ano/347519.shtml |title= Fallece 'Geo', uno de los cachorros de lince ib\u00e9rico nacido en cautividad este a\u00f1o |language= Spanish |trans-title=Death of 'Geo', one of this season's captive-born Iberian lynx cubs |first= David |last= Sierra |publisher= rtve.es |date=2010}}</ref>\u2014but the next year, breeding centers recorded 45 births with 26 surviving kittens.<ref name=ep120617>{{cite news |url= http://www.europapress.es/sociedad/medio-ambiente-00647/noticia-nacen-59-ejemplares-lince-temporada-programa-cria-cautividad-20120617133403.html |title= Nacen 59 ejemplares de lince esta temporada en el Programa de Cr\u00eda en Cautividad |language= Spanish |trans-title=59 lynx kittens born this season as part of the Captive Breeding Program |work= Europa Press |date= 17 June 2012}}</ref> In 2012, breeding centers in Portugal and Spain reported a total of 44 survivors from 59 births,<ref name=ep120617 /> while 2013 saw a total of 44 survivors out of 53 born.<ref name=efe130909>{{cite news |url= http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/1914672/0/programa-cria/lince-iberico/acaba-con-44-cachorros/ |title= El programa de cr\u00eda en cautividad del lince ib\u00e9rico acaba la temporada con 44 cachorros |language= Spanish |trans-title=The lynx captive breeding program ends the season with 44 cubs |work= EFE |publisher= 20minutos.es |date=2013 }}</ref> In 2017, the total population of Iberian lynx reached 475 specimens.<ref>{{cite web|title=El lince ib\u00e9rico ampl\u00eda sus dominios y alcanza los 475 ejemplares, pese a la falta de conejos y los atropellos|url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/natural/20170202/413902666216/lince.html|publisher=La Vanguardia|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, it was reported that Iberian lynx embryos and oocytes had been collected and preserved for the first time. They were collected from Saliega and another female\u2014both sterilized and retired from the breeding program\u2014by Berlin's Leibniz Institute for Zoo and Wildlife Research and stored in liquid nitrogen at the [[Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales]] in Madrid for possible future breeding.<ref name=fvb130323>{{cite news |url= http://phys.org/news/2013-03-iberian-lynx-embryos.html |title= For the first time Iberian lynx embryos are collected and preserved |work= Forschungsverbund Berlin e.V. (FVB) |publisher= phys.org |date=2013}}</ref> In July 2014, the MNCN-CSIC announced they had produced sperm cells from the testicular tissue of sexually immature lynx.<ref name=mundo140722>{{cite news |url= http://www.elmundo.es/ciencia/2014/07/22/53ce2d5dca4741f5328b4574.html |title= Esperma 'de laboratorio' para salvar al lince ib\u00e9rico |language= Spanish |trans-title=Laboratory-made sperm to save the Iberian lynx |first= E. |last=Mosquera Rodriguez |work= [[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |date=2014 }}</ref>\n\nIberian lynx can be observed in captivity only at the Jerez Zoo,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.zoobotanicojerez.com/index.php?id=1476 |title= The Iberian Lynx at the Zoobotanico de Jerez (in Spanish)}}</ref> since December 2014 at the [[Lisbon Zoo]],<ref name=observador211214>{{cite news |url= http://observador.pt/especiais/os-felinos-mais-ameacados-mundo-ja-moram-em-lisboa/# |title= Os felinos mais ameacados do mundo ja moram em Lisboa |language= Portuguese |trans-title=O casal de linces-ib\u00e9ricos chegou ao Jardim Zool\u00f3gico de Lisboa com uma miss\u00e3o especial: mostrar aos visitantes o que os torna os felinos mais amea\u00e7ados do mundo |first= V. |last= Novais |work= Observador |date=2014}}</ref> and since July 2016 at the [[Madrid Zoo]].<ref name=zoomadrid200716>{{cite news |url= http://zoomadrid.com/sala-de-prensa/llega-a-zoo-aquarium-de-madrid-una-pareja-de-linces-ibericos-del-proyecto-iberlince |title=Llega a Zoo Aquarium de Madrid una pareja de linces ib\u00e9ricos del proyecto Iberlince |work= Zoo Aquarium Madrid |date= 20 July 2016 }}</ref>\nThe [[Jerez de la Frontera|Jerez]] animals integrate the breeding program, the two Lisbon lynxes were formerly in the Portuguese breeding center but are no longer suited for the program (the female had multiple failed pregnancies and the male has a form of epilepsy),<ref name=ultimoreduto17032015>{{cite news |url= http://oultimoreduto.blogspot.pt/2015/03/nova-visita-ao-zoo-de-lisboa-o-lince.html/# |title= Nova Visita ao Zoo de Lisboa \u2013 O Lince Ib\u00e9rico |language= Portuguese |trans-title= New visit to the Lisbon Zoo \u2013 The Iberian Lynx |first= Filipe |last= Figueiredo |work= O \u00daltimo Reduto |date=2015 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160210100603/http://oultimoreduto.blogspot.pt/2015/03/nova-visita-ao-zoo-de-lisboa-o-lince.html |archive-date= 10 February 2016 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> and the two Madrid lynxes were equally retired from the breeding program for not being suited for reproduction.\n\n== Genetic research==\nThe [[genetic diversity]] of the Iberian lynx is lower than in any other genetically impoverished felid, which is possibly a consequence of fragmentation and isolation of population units.{{r|Casas2013}} Iberian lynxes in Do\u00f1ana and Andujar differ genetically at [[microsatellite]] markers. Samples collected in Do\u00f1ana exhibited a high degree of [[inbreeding]] as this unit was isolated for a long time.<ref name=Casas2013>{{cite journal |journal=Molecular Ecology |title=Genetics at the verge of extinction: insights from the Iberian lynx |author1=Casas-Marce, M. |author2=Soriano, L. |author3=L\u00f3pez-Bao, J. V. |author4=Godoy, J. A. |last-author-amp=yes |year=2013 |doi=10.1111/mec.12498 |pmid= 24128177 |volume=22 |issue=22 |pages=5503\u20135515}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Cats|Mammals}}\n* [[Bobcat]], ''Lynx rufus''\n* [[Canadian lynx]], ''Lynx canadensis''\n* [[Eurasian lynx]], ''Lynx lynx''\n* ''[[Felicola isidoroi]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Lynx pardinus}}\n{{Wikispecies|Lynx pardinus}}\n* [http://www.lcie.org/ Large Carnivore Initiative for Europe \u2013 Iberian lynx]\n* [http://www.lynxexsitu.es/ Programa de Conservaci\u00f3n Ex-Situ] Official Spanish government page {{in lang|es}}\n* [http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=98 Species portrait Iberian lynx; IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group]\n* ARKive \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20060506121156/http://www.arkive.org/species/GES/mammals/Lynx_pardinus/ Images and movies of the Iberian lynx (''Lynx pardinus)'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130529082338/http://www.iberianature.